WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.009 --> 00:00:01.973
Ed: Hello, everyone.

00:00:01.973 --> 00:00:03.845
Good evening.

00:00:03.845 --> 00:00:08.511
I'd like to welcome
you to the - (laughter)

00:00:08.511 --> 00:00:10.645
The MIT Club of California.

00:00:10.645 --> 00:00:14.452
Tonight, we have an excellent,
distinguished speaker,

00:00:14.452 --> 00:00:17.922
but before we introduce
him, I hope you have enjoyed

00:00:17.922 --> 00:00:20.479
the sandwiches and cookies.

00:00:20.479 --> 00:00:21.728
We learned to make those ourselves

00:00:21.728 --> 00:00:27.480
by watching one of
Sal's videos. (laughter)

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:31.068
Just kidding, they're
from Subway. (laughter)

00:00:34.224 --> 00:00:38.218
Let me read a bio for Sal.

00:00:39.198 --> 00:00:42.318
Sal is a social entrepreneur who
has become an internet sensation

00:00:42.318 --> 00:00:44.817
and inspiration for his fun

00:00:44.817 --> 00:00:47.984
and highly effective
educational videos on YouTube.

00:00:47.984 --> 00:00:49.942
Every month, more than 100,000 students,

00:00:49.942 --> 00:00:52.543
both young and old, across the globe,

00:00:52.543 --> 00:00:57.649
use his over 1,300 free videos
to learn about arithmetics,

00:00:57.649 --> 00:01:01.885
finance, chemistry,
(unintelligible) calculus.

00:01:01.885 --> 00:01:04.122
He founded the Khan Academy,
which was recently covered

00:01:04.122 --> 00:01:11.400
on CNN, PBS News, NPR, San Francisco
Chronicle, and NBC Nightline.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:13.322
His mission is nothing
short of creating a free

00:01:13.322 --> 00:01:16.319
and world class virtual school
for anyone in the world.

00:01:16.319 --> 00:01:18.985
He will speak about his
experience starting the academy

00:01:18.985 --> 00:01:24.567
and massively transformational
changes in learning and teaching.

00:01:24.567 --> 00:01:28.811
(unintelligible) in the
next five to ten years.

00:01:28.811 --> 00:01:31.223
Sal graduated from MIT in 1998

00:01:31.223 --> 00:01:33.263
with computer science and math degrees

00:01:33.263 --> 00:01:36.789
and received his MBA from
Harvard Business School.

00:01:36.789 --> 00:01:39.892
He left his day job as a
hedge fund analyst in 2009

00:01:39.892 --> 00:01:43.962
to dedicated full time to
his non-profit academy.

00:01:43.962 --> 00:01:48.597
We're delighted and honored to have
this distinguished speaker tonight,

00:01:48.597 --> 00:01:51.537
an emerging giant in the
online education space,

00:01:51.537 --> 00:01:55.514
a world-class educator,
a dynamic communicator,

00:01:55.514 --> 00:02:03.849
and a selfless good-doer,
Salman Khan. (applause)

00:02:03.849 --> 00:02:04.765
Sal: Can you all hear me?

00:02:04.765 --> 00:02:07.931
I'd prefer to just be
closer to you all, than ...

00:02:07.931 --> 00:02:09.680
Can you hear me in the back?

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:11.656
Okay, cool.

00:02:11.656 --> 00:02:14.959
Just like Ed said, I'm Sal,
the founder and faculty

00:02:14.959 --> 00:02:17.302
of the Khan Academy. (laughter)

00:02:17.302 --> 00:02:19.764
This is -

00:02:19.764 --> 00:02:23.536
I really want to make this -

00:02:23.536 --> 00:02:25.430
I think this will be a fun conversation.

00:02:25.430 --> 00:02:28.915
I don't want this to be me at the
PowerPoint for the whole hour.

00:02:28.915 --> 00:02:32.346
I really want you all to
interrupt me or raise your hand,

00:02:32.346 --> 00:02:34.511
ask me questions, and we can
take this wherever we want to go,

00:02:34.511 --> 00:02:36.680
because there's really a couple of
different conversations we can have

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:39.263
and maybe we can have them all.

00:02:39.263 --> 00:02:43.483
How many of you all have
watched a Khan Academy video?

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:44.990
Okay, that's a pretty good cover.

00:02:44.990 --> 00:02:47.462
Just so you know what it is, and actually,

00:02:47.462 --> 00:02:49.159
maybe to get a sense, of the growth.

00:02:49.159 --> 00:02:52.329
Ed said 100,000 and when he
first asked me it was 100,000,

00:02:52.329 --> 00:02:57.301
now it's 200,000 unique students a
month and it's only been two months.

00:02:57.301 --> 00:03:01.335
It is the fastest growing
open course effort.

00:03:01.335 --> 00:03:03.807
Now, it's actually passed up -

00:03:03.807 --> 00:03:05.533
I'm not - Well, I'm a little competitive.

00:03:05.533 --> 00:03:09.918
It passed up MIT recently,
in terms of (laughter)

00:03:09.918 --> 00:03:10.919
being the most used.

00:03:10.919 --> 00:03:13.669
It's getting about 60 or
70,000 video views a day.

00:03:13.669 --> 00:03:18.122
It has closed to 16
million views on YouTube.

00:03:19.768 --> 00:03:22.904
One of the things we can
talk about is maybe why.

00:03:22.904 --> 00:03:26.168
It might be something about the
content, how it's delivered and whatnot.

00:03:26.168 --> 00:03:27.904
We can talk about all of that.

00:03:27.904 --> 00:03:32.822
This is the site, just for those
of you all who have never seen it.

00:03:32.822 --> 00:03:35.544
We can also debate my
user interface skills

00:03:35.544 --> 00:03:43.285
for just putting all 1,400
links (laughter) on one page.

00:03:43.285 --> 00:03:47.221
Those are the videos and if
you click on a random video,

00:03:47.221 --> 00:03:54.510
if you want a review of
(unintelligible) you can click there.

00:03:54.510 --> 00:03:57.124
We can let it load up or whatever.

00:03:57.124 --> 00:03:59.261
That's the Khan Academy.

00:03:59.261 --> 00:04:03.227
What I want to do - (unintelligible)

00:04:14.343 --> 00:04:16.208
Is there sound?

00:04:16.208 --> 00:04:19.045
The sound isn't any different than
what you're hearing right now.

00:04:19.045 --> 00:04:24.845
(laughter) You see this and you
hear my voice and you don't see me.

00:04:24.845 --> 00:04:27.287
This'll give you a flavor
for the form factor.

00:04:27.287 --> 00:04:28.787
That could be a conversation we could have

00:04:28.787 --> 00:04:31.322
about why this is an interesting
form factor and why I did it

00:04:31.322 --> 00:04:33.793
and all of that type of thing.

00:04:33.793 --> 00:04:35.656
What I'm going to focus on,
because I think most people

00:04:35.656 --> 00:04:37.737
are familiar with the video library.

00:04:37.737 --> 00:04:40.156
It has this reach, it's gotten popular,

00:04:40.156 --> 00:04:44.406
it's growing 10 or 15%
a month at this point.

00:04:44.406 --> 00:04:46.546
I want to talk about the bigger vision.

00:04:46.546 --> 00:04:50.739
Ed has talked about this idea of
starting a virtual school for the world

00:04:50.739 --> 00:04:53.489
and obviously, videos are a start.

00:04:53.489 --> 00:04:55.521
They're the lecture part of a school,

00:04:55.521 --> 00:04:58.989
but a real school's got to
be more than just video.

00:04:58.989 --> 00:05:01.096
You have to have some
interaction with other people,

00:05:01.096 --> 00:05:03.322
you have to have practice,
you have to have assessment,

00:05:03.322 --> 00:05:05.632
you have to have data
and all of these things.

00:05:05.632 --> 00:05:09.103
That's what I want to talk about
and I'm generally open to ideas,

00:05:09.103 --> 00:05:10.604
because this is a work in progress.

00:05:10.604 --> 00:05:12.278
Some of it is starting to be built.

00:05:12.278 --> 00:05:15.822
Hopefully over the next few months
it'll be built in a much bigger way.

00:05:15.822 --> 00:05:18.073
Some volunteers have come out
of the woodwork very recently

00:05:18.073 --> 00:05:20.656
to supercharge some of these efforts.

00:05:20.656 --> 00:05:23.706
It's exciting times.

00:05:24.573 --> 00:05:28.206
Let me get the presentation up.

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:34.621
A good number of you all saw the videos.

00:05:34.621 --> 00:05:37.787
How many of you all saw the
web application on the site?

00:05:37.787 --> 00:05:41.159
Okay, that's a much
lower penetration rate.

00:05:41.159 --> 00:05:42.895
Just so you all know a
little bit of the history,

00:05:42.895 --> 00:05:45.037
and I'm happy to go into
this as much as you want,

00:05:45.037 --> 00:05:47.703
but I started doing
this remotely tutoring,

00:05:47.703 --> 00:05:50.455
because I was in Boston, my
cousins were in New Orleans,

00:05:50.455 --> 00:05:53.171
and she was having trouble
with units and I said,

00:05:53.171 --> 00:05:57.455
"Hey, after your school and my
work let's get together virtually.

00:05:57.455 --> 00:06:00.944
"We'll use Yahoo Doodle,
it'll be a shared notepad

00:06:00.944 --> 00:06:03.147
"that we can each see what
each other is writing."

00:06:03.147 --> 00:06:06.619
I got her a little Wacom pen
tablet, I had one for myself.

00:06:06.619 --> 00:06:09.430
We'd just do conference calls
and that's how I started.

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:11.132
Then she started doing really well,

00:06:11.132 --> 00:06:14.846
then I started tutoring her
brothers, other cousins.

00:06:14.846 --> 00:06:17.596
Then a couple of things happened

00:06:17.596 --> 00:06:18.972
and I usually go straight to the videos,

00:06:18.972 --> 00:06:23.375
because that's what it's known for,
but being a computer science geek,

00:06:23.375 --> 00:06:25.477
I didn't even think of
doing the videos at first.

00:06:25.477 --> 00:06:27.512
I said, "Hey, you know what,
I'm going to write soft -

00:06:27.512 --> 00:06:29.680
I would give them these little lectures

00:06:29.680 --> 00:06:32.783
and I would just point them
to random websites, like,

00:06:32.783 --> 00:06:34.954
"Hey, there's a cool applet
on that website over there.

00:06:34.954 --> 00:06:37.433
"Why don't you try it out and tell
me tomorrow whether you understood,

00:06:37.433 --> 00:06:40.673
"whether you're able to
do those exercises, or use
that website over there,"

00:06:40.673 --> 00:06:44.263
I just got really frustrated, this
piecemeal website here, website there,

00:06:44.263 --> 00:06:45.634
so I said, "I'm going to
write a couple of javascript,

00:06:45.634 --> 00:06:47.846
"little things that'll
generate problems for them."

00:06:47.846 --> 00:06:51.536
It's not just ten problems and it
may come up with some random numbers

00:06:51.536 --> 00:06:53.180
and give them as many
problems as they need.

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:54.955
I made a bunch of these modules.

00:06:54.955 --> 00:06:57.478
I'll show you what the modules look like.

00:06:58.096 --> 00:07:02.215
This is like a multiplying decimals module

00:07:02.215 --> 00:07:05.652
and we can go into as much
depth on these as you want.

00:07:05.652 --> 00:07:08.346
I started making these little
javascript modules for them

00:07:08.346 --> 00:07:11.157
and it was starting really where
she was, at units and basic algebra

00:07:11.157 --> 00:07:12.929
and adding and subtracting
negative numbers,

00:07:12.929 --> 00:07:16.629
and basic linear
equations and then I said,

00:07:16.629 --> 00:07:18.063
"Gee, you know, I don't trust -

00:07:18.063 --> 00:07:19.798
I'd say, "Hey, Nadia,
did you do the problems?

00:07:19.798 --> 00:07:20.732
"How many did you do?"

00:07:20.732 --> 00:07:23.969
and she's like, "Oh yeah, I did
them (unintelligible) (laughter)

00:07:23.969 --> 00:07:27.445
I was like, "I'm going to put
a database behind this thing."

00:07:27.445 --> 00:07:29.778
I put a database behind
it so I could keep track

00:07:29.778 --> 00:07:32.180
of when she did the problem,
how long was it taking her,

00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:33.948
how many times was she doing,

00:07:33.948 --> 00:07:36.420
how frequently was she getting
one right or one wrong.

00:07:36.420 --> 00:07:38.022
Then I started making them up.

00:07:38.022 --> 00:07:41.975
On that first slide right there,
each of these circles is a module,

00:07:41.975 --> 00:07:43.639
and literally, the first module -

00:07:43.639 --> 00:07:45.322
This was a very organic process.

00:07:45.322 --> 00:07:47.596
It was really just me working
with my cousins and iterating,

00:07:47.596 --> 00:07:49.604
saying it would be nice to have the data.

00:07:49.604 --> 00:07:52.937
Then, I started making
modules here one off

00:07:52.937 --> 00:07:55.139
and I would at first
just point them to it.

00:07:55.139 --> 00:07:58.242
Then after a while, I was like,
there's some kind of dependency here,

00:07:58.242 --> 00:08:01.044
because Nadia got that, but
she needs help with that,

00:08:01.044 --> 00:08:04.690
so to fill in that gap,
let me make another module.

00:08:04.690 --> 00:08:08.003
Then, after a while, I got tired
of having to assign the modules,

00:08:08.003 --> 00:08:10.953
so I said, "Well, it should
automatically assign the modules,

00:08:10.953 --> 00:08:13.752
"because once she gets
ten in a row in this,

00:08:13.752 --> 00:08:16.013
"she's ready for this, this, and this."

00:08:16.013 --> 00:08:19.585
So, I created this internal
dependency in the little app

00:08:19.585 --> 00:08:22.799
to do this and I said, "Well,
this is kind of a neat graph."

00:08:22.799 --> 00:08:24.469
This is what I was using just
to keep track of the modules,

00:08:24.469 --> 00:08:26.404
I should just expose this to the students,

00:08:26.404 --> 00:08:28.837
so they know what's going on.

00:08:28.837 --> 00:08:31.920
This is the app and this started
well before I made the first video,

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:34.143
but it's kind of like the
secret of the Khan Academy,

00:08:34.143 --> 00:08:36.944
so you're getting a little tidbit.

00:08:36.944 --> 00:08:39.717
But I think it's also the
future on a lot of levels.

00:08:39.717 --> 00:08:41.873
So this right here, this is
literally level one addition,

00:08:41.873 --> 00:08:43.761
so it's literally 1+1.

00:08:43.761 --> 00:08:46.264
If you go to the website,
there is literally a video

00:08:46.264 --> 00:08:53.436
on 1+1 and at first, it's almost
a joke that I made the video

00:08:53.436 --> 00:08:57.038
on adding 1+1, but the
whole idea behind it,

00:08:57.038 --> 00:09:01.445
besides being cute, is
to give people the notion

00:09:01.445 --> 00:09:05.081
that no matter how basic your
skills, you can go to this site

00:09:05.081 --> 00:09:09.371
and you will find something
that fits your need

00:09:09.371 --> 00:09:12.791
and the idea that you can, when
you see 1+1 on the same page

00:09:12.791 --> 00:09:15.560
as vector calculus, you're like,

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:21.332
"Gee, I just have to step through that
thing and I can get to vector calculus.

00:09:21.332 --> 00:09:24.113
"There's not some mysterious - (laughter)

00:09:24.113 --> 00:09:27.337
"And it's the same dude who's going
to take me through the - (laughter)

00:09:27.337 --> 00:09:29.408
"My Kindergarten teacher is
teaching me vector calculus."

00:09:29.408 --> 00:09:34.444
(laughter) You get ten in a row and -

00:09:34.444 --> 00:09:37.541
Once this was made, then
it started to make -

00:09:37.541 --> 00:09:39.704
This became what a lot of
people in education talk about,

00:09:39.704 --> 00:09:42.923
differentiated learning,
with data and all of that,

00:09:42.923 --> 00:09:46.840
but it made me pause and say,
"This is working for my cousins,"

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:48.547
but there was actually
one piece that was missing

00:09:48.547 --> 00:09:49.923
and that was the -

00:09:49.923 --> 00:09:51.381
I still had to do -

00:09:51.381 --> 00:09:55.220
When I first started it, I thought -

00:09:55.220 --> 00:09:57.340
It randomly generated these problems

00:09:57.340 --> 00:10:00.325
and picked random numbers here
and then when you clicked hint,

00:10:00.325 --> 00:10:02.924
it would show you the exact
steps for that problem.

00:10:02.924 --> 00:10:05.028
I was like, "Oh, that's all you
need to learn how to do a problem.

00:10:05.028 --> 00:10:06.966
"You just need the exact
steps for that exact problem.

00:10:06.966 --> 00:10:08.432
"This'll work for my cousins."

00:10:08.432 --> 00:10:09.366
But it didn't.

00:10:09.366 --> 00:10:12.371
It would help them if they kind of
knew how to multiply decimals already,

00:10:12.371 --> 00:10:14.256
but it didn't get them over that hurdle.

00:10:14.256 --> 00:10:17.309
I still had to do that one-on-one
session with them remotely.

00:10:17.309 --> 00:10:19.547
That became hard to scale.

00:10:19.547 --> 00:10:21.645
Literally, another buddy
from MIT, we were at dinner

00:10:21.645 --> 00:10:24.589
and he's like, "Why don't
you make YouTube videos?

00:10:24.589 --> 00:10:25.816
"The thing that you do with your cousins,

00:10:25.816 --> 00:10:27.721
"why don't you just
record that on YouTube?"

00:10:27.721 --> 00:10:29.673
I was completely dismissive of the idea.

00:10:29.673 --> 00:10:33.089
I was like, "Oh, that's so
silly, I have this software.

00:10:33.089 --> 00:10:36.493
"It generates problems
dynamically, (laughter)

00:10:36.493 --> 00:10:38.427
"it's got hints, what's a
YouTube video going to do?"

00:10:38.427 --> 00:10:40.673
He's like, "Yeah, you're right,
it's probably a stupid idea."

00:10:40.673 --> 00:10:42.066
(laughter) I went home and I was like,

00:10:42.066 --> 00:10:43.367
"Well, maybe there's something to it."

00:10:43.367 --> 00:10:46.258
Literally, when I kept recording
videos with my cousins,

00:10:46.258 --> 00:10:49.007
I would do the tenth lecture on
negative numbers with a new cousin,

00:10:49.007 --> 00:10:52.210
I was like, "Yeah, maybe a
YouTube video will make sense."

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:56.006
I made the first YouTube video
on greatest common divisor

00:10:56.006 --> 00:10:58.007
and this and that and then -

00:10:58.007 --> 00:11:01.584
I've said this in talks
before, the immediate feedback

00:11:01.584 --> 00:11:03.572
I got from my cousins was that,

00:11:03.572 --> 00:11:08.743
"You are better on YouTube
than you are live." (laughter)

00:11:08.743 --> 00:11:13.017
The point, I think, that he
was trying to communicate is

00:11:13.017 --> 00:11:16.713
it had none of the pressure of
a traditional tutoring session.

00:11:16.713 --> 00:11:20.076
"Did you get this?" and
you're staring at the person.

00:11:20.076 --> 00:11:23.685
They're like, "Yeah,
maybe I did," (laughter)

00:11:23.685 --> 00:11:27.189
and they're giving you bad information,
because they didn't get it.

00:11:27.189 --> 00:11:30.491
They feel bad pausing or repeating me,

00:11:30.491 --> 00:11:33.194
but they can do it all they
want with a YouTube video,

00:11:33.194 --> 00:11:36.992
or they can go to Wikipedia, or they
might be afraid of even admitting

00:11:36.992 --> 00:11:39.993
that they don't know how to
borrow or regroup or whatever,

00:11:39.993 --> 00:11:44.274
but now they can actually review
it in these one off videos.

00:11:44.274 --> 00:11:46.877
Then other people started
watching it, as well, and said,

00:11:46.877 --> 00:11:49.243
"Hey, there's something
there," and on top of that,

00:11:49.243 --> 00:11:51.881
I incorporated with this,
because that was the whole point

00:11:51.881 --> 00:11:55.215
in the first place, to have if you've
never seen this concept before,

00:11:55.215 --> 00:11:57.619
you at least have this
outlet, these YouTube videos

00:11:57.619 --> 00:12:01.122
that you could somehow access, but
before I go into the depths of this,

00:12:01.122 --> 00:12:02.890
I want to -

00:12:02.890 --> 00:12:07.409
Once this was built, then I had
this, "This seems to be working,

00:12:07.409 --> 00:12:12.244
"but let's compare it to what goes
on right now in the school system."

00:12:12.244 --> 00:12:17.262
If you think, the whole conversation
about education right now,

00:12:17.262 --> 00:12:20.596
it's all about the student-teacher ratios,

00:12:20.596 --> 00:12:23.596
how can we make the
inner city, poor schools

00:12:23.596 --> 00:12:27.764
look a lot like the fancy, rich
schools, give people computers,

00:12:27.764 --> 00:12:31.318
but no one is fundamentally
questioning the model.

00:12:31.318 --> 00:12:33.321
If you really think
about the model itself,

00:12:33.321 --> 00:12:36.826
I don't want to taint
your opinion before -

00:12:36.826 --> 00:12:38.994
It's bizarre.

00:12:38.994 --> 00:12:42.897
You have this situation,
you go to the classroom

00:12:42.897 --> 00:12:45.275
and you're all in a room together -

00:12:45.275 --> 00:12:47.525
We'll talk about what you could do
if you're all in a room together,

00:12:47.525 --> 00:12:49.071
but there's no interaction.

00:12:49.071 --> 00:12:51.940
It's just this broadcast
lecture, especially once you get

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:54.823
to the university level, but even
in the classroom in middle school.

00:12:54.823 --> 00:12:57.146
There might be a little
one question here or there,

00:12:57.146 --> 00:13:00.274
but fundamentally, it's a
broadcast lecture to the room.

00:13:00.274 --> 00:13:04.026
The teacher is pretty much
guaranteed to lose half the students,

00:13:04.026 --> 00:13:06.489
or bore half the students,
and at some point,

00:13:06.489 --> 00:13:07.898
they're going to switch the whole time.

00:13:07.898 --> 00:13:13.186
You do that, then the student has
to go home, do their homework.

00:13:13.186 --> 00:13:14.451
They do it in a complete vacuum.

00:13:14.451 --> 00:13:16.856
They have a textbook, every other problem

00:13:16.856 --> 00:13:18.658
there's a solution in
the back, you don't know

00:13:18.658 --> 00:13:21.600
why you got it right or wrong, anything.

00:13:21.600 --> 00:13:23.269
You don't have anyone to help you.

00:13:23.269 --> 00:13:24.305
If you're lucky you might get a tutor

00:13:24.305 --> 00:13:26.042
or a parent might be able to help you.

00:13:26.042 --> 00:13:27.901
Then you go to the class the next day

00:13:27.901 --> 00:13:30.844
and there might be some
type of review of homework

00:13:30.844 --> 00:13:32.780
or something, but really no real feedback

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:34.069
and the cycle repeats itself.

00:13:34.069 --> 00:13:35.734
You get another lecture,
then you go back home,

00:13:35.734 --> 00:13:37.051
you do homework in a
vacuum, and this whole time

00:13:37.051 --> 00:13:38.551
you don't know what you're doing at all.

00:13:38.551 --> 00:13:40.402
The teacher has no data, nothing.

00:13:40.402 --> 00:13:42.273
That occurs for a couple of days

00:13:42.273 --> 00:13:44.952
and then, bam, you have an assessment.

00:13:44.952 --> 00:13:53.368
The assessment, some students
get 50%, 80%, 70%, 90%.

00:13:53.368 --> 00:13:56.506
The good students get 95%, next concept.

00:13:56.506 --> 00:14:00.202
Even if you fail an
exam, the class moves on.

00:14:00.202 --> 00:14:02.848
You don't know half of the
subject, half of the material

00:14:02.848 --> 00:14:05.982
in that previous concept and
the class is going to move on.

00:14:05.982 --> 00:14:07.585
You might say that failing student's bad

00:14:07.585 --> 00:14:08.786
and the A students are all right,

00:14:08.786 --> 00:14:11.119
but they still didn't
know 5% of the concept.

00:14:11.119 --> 00:14:14.035
Maybe it was a careless mistake,
but maybe they didn't know

00:14:14.035 --> 00:14:16.227
what happens when you take
something to the zeroth power.

00:14:16.227 --> 00:14:19.565
Maybe they didn't know exactly
what a fractional exponent was,

00:14:19.565 --> 00:14:21.398
that one problem on the exam
with the fractional exponent.

00:14:21.398 --> 00:14:26.702
That A student, the one who's
getting the positive label,

00:14:26.702 --> 00:14:29.030
when they go to calculus
and they see that,

00:14:29.030 --> 00:14:30.568
what are they going to do?

00:14:30.568 --> 00:14:32.543
They're not going to get 95%,
they're going to get 90%,

00:14:32.543 --> 00:14:34.504
because they're going to miss
that and another concept.

00:14:34.504 --> 00:14:38.174
That's not even to mention about the 50%.

00:14:38.174 --> 00:14:39.126
You have this bizarre -

00:14:39.126 --> 00:14:41.376
The first time you get
assessment is when it's time

00:14:41.376 --> 00:14:42.910
to move to the next concept.

00:14:42.910 --> 00:14:44.404
In no way is it actionable.

00:14:44.404 --> 00:14:45.846
If you really think about the process,

00:14:45.846 --> 00:14:48.814
it's just this huge filtering mechanism.

00:14:48.814 --> 00:14:52.020
It's just this process
where every step of the way

00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:53.710
we're just knocking
more and more people off

00:14:53.710 --> 00:14:56.543
and the lucky people in this
room, we were the people

00:14:56.543 --> 00:14:59.958
who happened to be lucky
enough that we were assessed

00:14:59.958 --> 00:15:01.876
and filtered at the right
place at the right time

00:15:01.876 --> 00:15:05.101
and that led to us feeling really
smart and going on. (laughter)

00:15:05.101 --> 00:15:08.005
That's the way it works.

00:15:08.005 --> 00:15:09.102
It makes you really question -

00:15:09.102 --> 00:15:12.067
We're all lucky. (laughter)

00:15:12.067 --> 00:15:14.510
That's the big takeaway.

00:15:14.510 --> 00:15:17.876
What's happening here, what
I think is happening here,

00:15:17.876 --> 00:15:22.017
is that whole cycle, it's
all happening instantaneously

00:15:22.017 --> 00:15:23.876
with every interaction.

00:15:23.876 --> 00:15:26.458
The instruction, if you've never seen

00:15:26.458 --> 00:15:29.494
multiplying decimals before in
your life, you click "watch video",

00:15:29.494 --> 00:15:31.875
it pumps in from YouTube,
and you can imagine

00:15:31.875 --> 00:15:35.128
there's one or two videos right now,
but you eventually have ten videos,

00:15:35.128 --> 00:15:37.043
you're tracking whether the
person watched the video,

00:15:37.043 --> 00:15:39.232
you can eventually track
whether they paused or repeated,

00:15:39.232 --> 00:15:41.068
where they watched, and I'll
talk more about that later on,

00:15:41.068 --> 00:15:42.789
how you can perfect the content.

00:15:42.789 --> 00:15:46.107
They get the instruction there,
then they can do the practice,

00:15:46.107 --> 00:15:48.542
so you're giving them practice
and you get immediate feedback.

00:15:48.542 --> 00:15:49.977
Did I get it right or wrong?

00:15:49.977 --> 00:15:52.620
If you don't know how to do it, you
get the exact steps for that problem

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:54.585
and then you're also getting assessment,

00:15:54.585 --> 00:15:56.421
because every time you do a problem,

00:15:56.421 --> 00:15:57.918
it's tracking everything about that.

00:15:57.918 --> 00:15:59.538
When you did it, how long it took you,

00:15:59.538 --> 00:16:03.037
how many times did you click "hint",

00:16:03.037 --> 00:16:05.495
and then the paradigm here, and I
literally did this just on a whim,

00:16:05.495 --> 00:16:08.453
I was just like, "How do I know if
someone really knows something?"

00:16:08.453 --> 00:16:12.873
It's not 90%, or it's not 95%, just keep
doing it until you get ten in a row.

00:16:12.873 --> 00:16:14.833
Ten in a row should be the paradigm,

00:16:14.833 --> 00:16:17.538
because then that will enforce
a certain level of discipline.

00:16:17.538 --> 00:16:18.789
People say, "Oh isn't that -

00:16:18.789 --> 00:16:21.610
No, when you take the SAT, you can't make

00:16:21.610 --> 00:16:23.188
those little careless mistakes.

00:16:23.188 --> 00:16:25.779
You should enforce a
certain level of precision.

00:16:25.779 --> 00:16:27.438
I just threw out ten in a row.

00:16:27.438 --> 00:16:29.205
It doesn't have to be ten in a
row, it could be five in a row,

00:16:29.205 --> 00:16:31.454
or whatever, depending on the concept,

00:16:31.454 --> 00:16:34.854
but if you think about what's
happening when you enforce it

00:16:34.854 --> 00:16:37.789
is you don't allow that
95% student to move on

00:16:37.789 --> 00:16:42.453
while not knowing that 5% and then
only get lost in the next topic.

00:16:42.453 --> 00:16:44.899
That's the general idea.

00:16:44.899 --> 00:16:46.403
This right here is the -

00:16:46.403 --> 00:16:48.370
This is just another example of a module.

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:49.745
This is slope of a line.

00:16:49.745 --> 00:16:52.703
If you don't know how to do, just do
"hint" and it draws things for you.

00:16:52.703 --> 00:16:54.144
It's just another indication of -

00:16:54.144 --> 00:16:55.611
All of this is live.

00:16:55.611 --> 00:16:57.813
You can go right now to
KhanExercises.appspot.com

00:16:57.813 --> 00:17:00.120
and you can try out all of
this stuff and I encourage you

00:17:00.120 --> 00:17:01.517
if you have friends or family members.

00:17:01.517 --> 00:17:03.202
There was even a guy at the
hedge fund I worked with

00:17:03.202 --> 00:17:05.254
who was going to take the GMAT
and he was summa cum laude

00:17:05.254 --> 00:17:09.260
from Yale and he's like,
"What should I use for math?"

00:17:09.260 --> 00:17:10.591
"You should use this."

00:17:10.591 --> 00:17:12.205
He was like, "Hey, but this
is starting me at 1+1."

00:17:12.205 --> 00:17:13.999
I said, "Just do it."

00:17:13.999 --> 00:17:15.794
Two weeks later, he was like,
"That was good." (laughter)

00:17:15.794 --> 00:17:21.538
It's amazing how long many people
haven't multiplied decimals. (laughter)

00:17:21.538 --> 00:17:26.674
That's the self-paced
student view of the world.

00:17:26.674 --> 00:17:29.945
I still haven't given you
the whole virtual school.

00:17:29.945 --> 00:17:32.249
Right now we're talking about videos

00:17:32.249 --> 00:17:34.684
and then we've kind of automated
the self-directed learning

00:17:34.684 --> 00:17:37.873
and learning at your own
pace and getting assessed,

00:17:37.873 --> 00:17:39.988
but then you have to think about
how can you incorporate that

00:17:39.988 --> 00:17:41.704
with the human experience.

00:17:41.704 --> 00:17:45.526
You're coming into a room
together to essentially learn

00:17:45.526 --> 00:17:48.609
how can you use this technology
to hyper charge that?

00:17:48.609 --> 00:17:51.400
Actually, before I even talk about this,

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:54.637
there's actually a very simple
flipping of the classroom

00:17:54.637 --> 00:17:55.941
that I think should occur tomorrow.

00:17:55.941 --> 00:17:58.691
You don't need any of this software,
because the videos already exist

00:17:58.691 --> 00:18:00.192
and some teachers - It wasn't my idea -

00:18:00.192 --> 00:18:02.859
A teacher in London said that he is now -

00:18:02.859 --> 00:18:04.311
If you think, it's actually a no-brainer.

00:18:04.311 --> 00:18:06.650
I don't understand why this
doesn't happen worldwide tomorrow.

00:18:06.650 --> 00:18:10.776
He is now assigning the
lectures for homework

00:18:10.776 --> 00:18:12.920
and he's having the students
do homework in the classroom.

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:14.559
There's no other technology necessary.

00:18:14.559 --> 00:18:16.108
Think about what happens there.

00:18:16.108 --> 00:18:21.731
Right now, we all gather at
seven in the morning in 10250

00:18:21.731 --> 00:18:26.167
and we're all with our
peers and (unintelligible)

00:18:26.167 --> 00:18:30.109
We have to sit passively and
just get this broadcast lecture

00:18:30.109 --> 00:18:31.753
and then we go off on our own

00:18:31.753 --> 00:18:34.011
and we do these problem sets in a vacuum.

00:18:34.011 --> 00:18:36.096
If you flip the model and
the lecture, as we said,

00:18:36.096 --> 00:18:38.413
is one size fits all, I
might be lost or bored,

00:18:38.413 --> 00:18:40.443
I might have gaps from the last
lecture that I didn't understand,

00:18:40.443 --> 00:18:42.526
but I still have to
get this exact lecture.

00:18:42.526 --> 00:18:47.338
You flip the model, you get
on-demand video at home,

00:18:47.338 --> 00:18:50.831
when you're ready for
it, when you're awake.

00:18:50.831 --> 00:18:56.055
I got a letter from a student
about they did actually have

00:18:56.055 --> 00:18:58.554
a good calculus teacher, but
he had two rows in front of him

00:18:58.554 --> 00:19:02.471
this really cute girl and every
day he's just trying to figure out

00:19:02.471 --> 00:19:06.916
how he can ask her out and he missed
two months of calculus. (laughter)

00:19:06.916 --> 00:19:08.637
This was his only -

00:19:09.436 --> 00:19:11.020
(laughter)

00:19:16.189 --> 00:19:20.972
I say that's a story of another
person, but - (laughter)

00:19:21.879 --> 00:19:25.079
We all had similar stories. (laughter)

00:19:26.841 --> 00:19:29.530
We go home and we do these
problem sets in a complete vacuum.

00:19:29.530 --> 00:19:31.532
We have no one to help
us, but if you flip it,

00:19:31.532 --> 00:19:33.565
you can watch things at your
own pace, fill in your gaps,

00:19:33.565 --> 00:19:35.990
do whatever you need and then
when you're in the classroom,

00:19:35.990 --> 00:19:40.038
you have 30 or 40 or 400
of your peers to help you

00:19:40.038 --> 00:19:41.657
and you have the professor
who can walk around

00:19:41.657 --> 00:19:43.656
and in real time, see
how people are doing,

00:19:43.656 --> 00:19:46.310
two weeks before the
assessment, two weeks before

00:19:46.310 --> 00:19:48.380
everyone gets that label
placed on their head

00:19:48.380 --> 00:19:51.284
that they're a B student.

00:19:51.284 --> 00:19:54.073
If you really think about it,
honestly, and I'm not this touchy -

00:19:54.073 --> 00:19:57.203
These people who are
anti-grades and that's like,

00:19:57.203 --> 00:19:58.823
oh, that's touchy feely.

00:19:58.823 --> 00:20:01.240
I'm anti-grades because
I think it's ridiculous.

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:02.823
It's not about -

00:20:02.823 --> 00:20:06.866
It's because if you're a
B student, you shouldn't -

00:20:06.866 --> 00:20:08.933
Everyone should be forced
to be an A student.

00:20:08.933 --> 00:20:10.239
It's on that concept.

00:20:10.239 --> 00:20:12.303
It's silly, you'll meet many, many people,

00:20:12.303 --> 00:20:13.938
and I think this room is an exception,

00:20:13.938 --> 00:20:15.156
but you'll meet many, many people who went

00:20:15.156 --> 00:20:18.811
through algebra, algebra
two, geometry, pre-calculus,

00:20:18.811 --> 00:20:21.906
trigonometry, calculus, and
when they see an algebra problem

00:20:21.906 --> 00:20:25.453
in front of their face, they don't see it.

00:20:25.453 --> 00:20:28.489
They have never had mastery
of anything in between

00:20:28.489 --> 00:20:32.073
and this whole exercise of
going from one hoop to the next

00:20:32.073 --> 00:20:34.240
and being an A- student the whole way,

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:36.628
it's just an exercise in
filtering, it's not an exercise

00:20:36.628 --> 00:20:39.199
in actually making people
have tangible skills

00:20:39.199 --> 00:20:41.301
that they can do
something productive with.

00:20:41.301 --> 00:20:44.103
What I just described, flipping the model,

00:20:44.103 --> 00:20:45.804
that's if you have no technology,

00:20:45.804 --> 00:20:48.275
but if you have the technology,
what you can do is teach -

00:20:48.275 --> 00:20:51.240
There's a bunch of student
names here that you can't see,

00:20:51.240 --> 00:20:55.047
I've blanked them out, but this is
a report that a teacher could have

00:20:55.047 --> 00:20:57.983
and this is actually a real report,
this isn't a Photoshop version.

00:20:57.983 --> 00:21:00.120
This was at a summer camp where they used

00:21:00.120 --> 00:21:01.657
what I showed you in
the last couple slides

00:21:01.657 --> 00:21:04.724
as their math curriculum,
where every student was able

00:21:04.724 --> 00:21:08.863
to work at their own pace and
the teacher walks in every day.

00:21:08.863 --> 00:21:11.490
Each column here is one of those modules

00:21:11.490 --> 00:21:14.534
that we saw on that first
slide, one of those concepts.

00:21:14.534 --> 00:21:16.534
Each row here is a student.

00:21:16.534 --> 00:21:19.157
Green means the student already
got ten in a row on that concept.

00:21:19.157 --> 00:21:21.372
They did it, they're cool.

00:21:21.372 --> 00:21:24.075
Purple means that they're
working on it right now,

00:21:24.075 --> 00:21:27.573
that that's their frontier
of learning at the moment.

00:21:27.573 --> 00:21:30.074
Everything seems to be going okay.

00:21:30.074 --> 00:21:33.927
Red means that students done 50 problems.

00:21:33.927 --> 00:21:35.548
Sometimes you can think of the heuristic.

00:21:35.548 --> 00:21:37.413
That student's done 50 problems,

00:21:37.413 --> 00:21:39.300
95% of students who have done 50 problems

00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:40.636
in that module usually move on.

00:21:40.636 --> 00:21:41.997
This student has not.

00:21:41.997 --> 00:21:43.872
Some type of intervention should occur,

00:21:43.872 --> 00:21:45.164
some type of human intervention.

00:21:45.164 --> 00:21:47.700
A teacher could look at this and
either they could eyeball it.

00:21:47.700 --> 00:21:49.309
They could say, "Hey,
look, everyone's doing fine

00:21:49.309 --> 00:21:51.780
"but these two kids need
help in level two division.

00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:53.688
"Let everyone else work at their own pace,

00:21:53.688 --> 00:21:55.615
" let me just take
these two students aside

00:21:55.615 --> 00:21:58.086
"and do a very intimate,
focused intervention

00:21:58.086 --> 00:21:59.142
"on just those two students."

00:21:59.142 --> 00:22:01.642
Even better, you can pair
these two students up

00:22:01.642 --> 00:22:03.579
with these two students initially

00:22:03.579 --> 00:22:04.928
and see if that gets them over the hurdle.

00:22:04.928 --> 00:22:08.141
You can actually capture the
data before and after that.

00:22:08.141 --> 00:22:09.964
I'm not there yet, but if the software

00:22:09.964 --> 00:22:11.893
is actually scheduling the interactions,

00:22:11.893 --> 00:22:13.474
you can actually see
what happens before those

00:22:13.474 --> 00:22:16.474
and start to rank teachers and
students and all of that type of thing.

00:22:16.474 --> 00:22:19.474
Slowly work up to the
level of the teacher.

00:22:19.474 --> 00:22:24.445
What I think should happen and
hope that this catalyzes it

00:22:24.445 --> 00:22:27.224
is we go back to a one-room schoolhouse.

00:22:27.224 --> 00:22:30.517
We go back to room full of
people, from Kindergartners

00:22:30.517 --> 00:22:32.559
all the way to anybody.

00:22:32.559 --> 00:22:35.309
Senior citizens who want
to come back and learn

00:22:35.309 --> 00:22:37.974
and they're all working at their own pace

00:22:37.974 --> 00:22:42.308
and if you have trouble with a
concept, even if you don't know,

00:22:42.308 --> 00:22:44.498
this will know if you having
trouble with a concept.

00:22:44.498 --> 00:22:47.667
It will pair you with somebody else
and it'll know about that interaction,

00:22:47.667 --> 00:22:49.891
it'll know how good of an
instructor that person was

00:22:49.891 --> 00:22:52.807
before and after, you'll
rate them, whatever else.

00:22:52.807 --> 00:22:54.724
Then, you can keep escalating
up and up the ladder

00:22:54.724 --> 00:22:56.474
until eventually you can
get by the paid teacher.

00:22:56.474 --> 00:22:58.179
You can actually have a reality where -

00:22:58.179 --> 00:23:00.047
Obviously there's a huge aspect

00:23:00.047 --> 00:23:02.058
of actually teaching people for retention.

00:23:02.058 --> 00:23:04.417
This isn't just a way to
get economics and scale.

00:23:04.417 --> 00:23:06.229
This whole mechanism, I'm a ninth grader

00:23:06.229 --> 00:23:08.623
and I'm teaching a sixth
grader negative numbers.

00:23:08.623 --> 00:23:11.224
That, by itself, is a
hugely powerful tool.

00:23:11.224 --> 00:23:12.974
I'm learning things better
than I ever learned before

00:23:12.974 --> 00:23:14.122
just doing these videos.

00:23:14.122 --> 00:23:15.309
You can imagine if you're -

00:23:15.309 --> 00:23:16.497
And this whole level of maturity.

00:23:16.497 --> 00:23:17.887
I think, actually, if
you hang out with people

00:23:17.887 --> 00:23:19.567
older and younger than yourself,
you actually act more mature

00:23:19.567 --> 00:23:21.876
for a whole set of reasons.

00:23:21.876 --> 00:23:23.938
Then, all of a sudden, you have a
model, where everyone is learning,

00:23:23.938 --> 00:23:26.407
the classroom is actually
an interactive experience,

00:23:26.407 --> 00:23:29.533
it's no longer a passive
experience, everyone is operating

00:23:29.533 --> 00:23:31.246
exactly at the level that they need to,

00:23:31.246 --> 00:23:33.712
and it actually scales.

00:23:33.712 --> 00:23:35.200
You can actually make it economic.

00:23:35.200 --> 00:23:36.317
You could actually have -

00:23:36.317 --> 00:23:38.753
Everyone's obsessed with
student-teacher ratios,

00:23:38.753 --> 00:23:40.783
but student-teacher ratios assume a model

00:23:40.783 --> 00:23:43.658
that if there's one of me and ten of you,

00:23:43.658 --> 00:23:44.950
then we can have a conversation.

00:23:44.950 --> 00:23:46.060
If there's one of me and 20 of you,

00:23:46.060 --> 00:23:47.395
we're going to have
less of a conversation.

00:23:47.395 --> 00:23:48.562
If there's one of me and 100 of you,

00:23:48.562 --> 00:23:49.616
we're not going to have a conversation.

00:23:49.616 --> 00:23:51.365
That's true, to some degree, but here,

00:23:51.365 --> 00:23:52.949
everyone works at their own pace.

00:23:52.949 --> 00:23:55.069
Even if there's 100
students and one paid tutor,

00:23:55.069 --> 00:23:58.339
because you have this
interaction, I'm willing to bet

00:23:58.339 --> 00:23:59.741
that you're going to
have a better interaction

00:23:59.741 --> 00:24:02.443
with that one paid teacher who
can now be paid 100 grand a year,

00:24:02.443 --> 00:24:04.533
instead of what teachers get paid.

00:24:04.533 --> 00:24:06.533
You're going to have a better
interaction in this world

00:24:06.533 --> 00:24:08.535
with a 100:1 student-teacher
ratio, than you'd probably get

00:24:08.535 --> 00:24:14.320
in even the fanciest private
schools that there are right now.

00:24:15.165 --> 00:24:19.836
This right here, this is
literally the summer program

00:24:19.836 --> 00:24:21.311
had asked about this and
I was curious myself.

00:24:21.311 --> 00:24:23.245
This was literally me just
doing sequel queries in the data

00:24:23.245 --> 00:24:27.082
every night from the summer camp.

00:24:27.082 --> 00:24:30.653
It's not like a rigorous study,
but to me, it speaks to the power

00:24:30.653 --> 00:24:32.531
of every student working at their own pace

00:24:32.531 --> 00:24:36.364
and throws into question, the
traditional notions of assessment,

00:24:36.364 --> 00:24:40.164
which we, I think, sense are
(unintelligible) to begin with.

00:24:40.164 --> 00:24:43.531
What this chart is doing,
this axis right here

00:24:43.531 --> 00:24:45.281
is the days in the summer camp.

00:24:45.281 --> 00:24:47.571
It was a six-week program
and this is just a count

00:24:47.571 --> 00:24:49.515
of the modules completed.

00:24:49.515 --> 00:24:52.614
This black line right here, that's
the class mean, the class average.

00:24:52.614 --> 00:24:57.364
On day seven in this class
of 30 or so students,

00:24:57.364 --> 00:25:00.365
the average student has
completed 23 modules.

00:25:00.365 --> 00:25:01.852
That's what that tells us.

00:25:01.852 --> 00:25:04.365
You can actually even see
that they all started at 1+1.

00:25:04.365 --> 00:25:05.826
It was actually an interesting idea,

00:25:05.826 --> 00:25:07.322
because we started
another group not at 1+1

00:25:07.322 --> 00:25:10.260
and some subset of the
students always got stuck.

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:12.330
They just never moved on, even
though we started them at fifth grade

00:25:12.330 --> 00:25:14.948
and they were seventh graders,
some subset always got stuck.

00:25:14.948 --> 00:25:18.115
We saw when we started everyone
at 1+1, no one got stuck,

00:25:18.115 --> 00:25:20.865
which tells you that there
are some smart people

00:25:20.865 --> 00:25:25.281
who have some gaps and it
never gets addressed otherwise.

00:25:25.281 --> 00:25:27.364
You can have the best
algebra teacher on the planet

00:25:27.364 --> 00:25:29.614
and you can have an innately
very intelligent kid,

00:25:29.614 --> 00:25:33.198
but if he or she just is a little
foggy on multiplying decimals,

00:25:33.198 --> 00:25:36.220
there's no hope, they're just
going to talk past each other

00:25:36.220 --> 00:25:38.031
and it's just going to be a
very frustrating experience.

00:25:38.031 --> 00:25:40.531
When we started everyone at
1+1, and you see it here.

00:25:40.531 --> 00:25:42.995
It's a very steep curve,
this is the review.

00:25:42.995 --> 00:25:45.095
This was the kids just getting ten
in row, ten in row, ten in a row.

00:25:45.095 --> 00:25:46.660
Then it starts to level out a bit.

00:25:46.660 --> 00:25:49.099
This is, you can see
the learning happening.

00:25:49.099 --> 00:25:51.031
The interesting thing, at least to me,

00:25:51.031 --> 00:25:53.236
the interesting thing about
this is the green lines

00:25:53.236 --> 00:25:55.030
are standard deviation
above and below that mean.

00:25:55.030 --> 00:25:58.985
You can plot all the students here,
but this student in particular,

00:25:58.985 --> 00:26:02.879
on day five, if you did a
pre-assessment for the class,

00:26:02.879 --> 00:26:07.722
if you did an assessment right
here, he only completed 12 modules.

00:26:07.722 --> 00:26:09.604
More than one standard
deviation below the mean.

00:26:09.604 --> 00:26:11.852
If you were in the traditional,
if you were tracking students,

00:26:11.852 --> 00:26:13.625
you'd say, "Oh, she's a remedial student,

00:26:13.625 --> 00:26:14.769
"she's going to hold the class back,

00:26:14.769 --> 00:26:16.438
"or we have to hold the rest
of the class back for her.

00:26:16.438 --> 00:26:18.128
"She doesn't belong in here," all that

00:26:18.128 --> 00:26:20.101
and you would put a big
label on her forehead.

00:26:20.101 --> 00:26:24.152
"You're never going to be an
engineer," and all of these things

00:26:24.152 --> 00:26:26.219
and actually it does happen
around sixth or seventh grade.

00:26:26.219 --> 00:26:30.942
That is when these labels, these
careers get ruled out for students.

00:26:30.942 --> 00:26:32.559
Because she was able to spend a little -

00:26:32.559 --> 00:26:34.993
I was curious, I was like,
"What happened to her?"

00:26:34.993 --> 00:26:37.822
and I could go into the data and I
could see exactly what she was doing.

00:26:37.822 --> 00:26:39.329
She was spending more
time than everyone else

00:26:39.329 --> 00:26:41.133
on adding and subtracting
negative numbers.

00:26:41.133 --> 00:26:43.942
Just to understand this
chart right here, each bar,

00:26:43.942 --> 00:26:45.172
this is the first problem she did.

00:26:45.172 --> 00:26:49.441
Red is wrong, blue is right, and
the height is how long it took her.

00:26:49.441 --> 00:26:51.810
This is just from the
data of the interaction.

00:26:51.810 --> 00:26:54.079
You can see she got a
couple of questions wrong,

00:26:54.079 --> 00:26:55.813
then she maybe guessed one right,

00:26:55.813 --> 00:26:57.983
then you have this big long time
she actually watched the video here.

00:26:57.983 --> 00:26:59.191
I looked at the video log.

00:26:59.191 --> 00:27:01.656
She watched the video here, then
she got a couple more right,

00:27:01.656 --> 00:27:03.422
but then she still got a few wrong.

00:27:03.422 --> 00:27:05.441
Once again, in a traditional classroom,

00:27:05.441 --> 00:27:10.329
she would have been said, "Oh, at
this point you are an A student.

00:27:10.329 --> 00:27:13.231
"You got nine of ten right,
or you got 19/20 right

00:27:13.231 --> 00:27:15.899
"and you're an A student,"
and force her to keep going.

00:27:15.899 --> 00:27:18.979
A couple more right, one wrong,
then finally she got ten in a row.

00:27:18.979 --> 00:27:21.205
You can actually see that
she also got faster on it.

00:27:21.205 --> 00:27:22.773
There's a whole other element of speed,

00:27:22.773 --> 00:27:24.976
which does matter on
some standardized tests.

00:27:24.976 --> 00:27:27.246
Once she got through
that, once she was able

00:27:27.246 --> 00:27:28.522
to just remediate herself

00:27:28.522 --> 00:27:31.942
and really build a strong
foundation, she just raced ahead.

00:27:31.942 --> 00:27:33.023
This was just in six weeks.

00:27:33.023 --> 00:27:35.086
She went from being the second
to worst student in the class,

00:27:35.086 --> 00:27:38.056
if you want to measure that way,
to the second to third best.

00:27:38.056 --> 00:27:39.608
All the students are on the chart here.

00:27:39.608 --> 00:27:40.733
In just six weeks.

00:27:40.733 --> 00:27:42.774
It makes you question, if
you did an assessment here,

00:27:42.774 --> 00:27:45.191
and I show that because
she literally raced

00:27:45.191 --> 00:27:50.234
through level three linear
equations, which is like 2x+7=-3x-4

00:27:50.234 --> 00:27:53.173
and she just thought it was intuitive
after doing maybe level two.

00:27:53.173 --> 00:27:54.192
She just raced.

00:27:54.192 --> 00:27:55.809
If you saw that student,
you'd say, "Oh, she's gifted."

00:27:55.809 --> 00:28:00.692
(laughter) It makes you really question.

00:28:00.692 --> 00:28:04.275
We were just the lucky kids that
got assessed at the right time

00:28:04.275 --> 00:28:07.749
and got all positive feedback and
we were assessed at that point,

00:28:07.749 --> 00:28:10.555
but there's probably a lot of
people who might've been able

00:28:10.555 --> 00:28:13.559
to eat our lunch eventually,
who got kicked off.

00:28:17.158 --> 00:28:19.998
This, I show this, this
is data from YouTube.

00:28:19.998 --> 00:28:23.608
I think everything I talked about before

00:28:23.608 --> 00:28:26.003
is how do you make sure
a student learns properly

00:28:26.003 --> 00:28:28.192
and how do you make sure that
their foundation is built

00:28:28.192 --> 00:28:29.976
and how do you use that data to optimize

00:28:29.976 --> 00:28:32.847
the actual physical
interactions, but I show this

00:28:32.847 --> 00:28:36.263
to show that there's another dimension
of perfecting the actual content.

00:28:36.263 --> 00:28:37.598
This is data that YouTube gives me.

00:28:37.598 --> 00:28:39.889
They call this audience attention.

00:28:39.889 --> 00:28:42.014
What they do is they
measure the drop off rate

00:28:42.014 --> 00:28:44.097
off of a YouTube video relative

00:28:44.097 --> 00:28:45.933
to the average YouTube
video of that length.

00:28:45.933 --> 00:28:47.792
Let's say the average
YouTube video at minute three

00:28:47.792 --> 00:28:49.848
has lost 40% of its audience.

00:28:49.848 --> 00:28:52.262
That's just a natural drop off rate.

00:28:52.262 --> 00:28:55.734
At minute three, if I've
lost 40% of my audience,

00:28:55.734 --> 00:28:57.513
I'll be hugging the line right there.

00:28:57.513 --> 00:29:00.430
If I've only lost 20% of my
audience, I'll be above average.

00:29:00.430 --> 00:29:02.431
That's what they're measuring
there, but you can imagine -

00:29:02.431 --> 00:29:07.346
Actually, I've seen a few of my
videos where this curve does this.

00:29:07.346 --> 00:29:08.930
It just drops off.

00:29:08.930 --> 00:29:11.383
I can go at that exact
minute in the video and see,

00:29:11.383 --> 00:29:14.720
Oh, I said orthogonality and
I never defined orthogonality.

00:29:14.720 --> 00:29:18.122
I can either re-record the video,
I could put a little bubble there,

00:29:18.122 --> 00:29:20.098
where you can get more information.

00:29:20.098 --> 00:29:25.030
You're getting real data that
allows you to actually iterate

00:29:25.030 --> 00:29:26.713
and perfect on what you're producing

00:29:26.713 --> 00:29:28.414
and you can imagine two
dimensions, this is attention.

00:29:28.414 --> 00:29:32.329
You could also have efficacy, if you
couple it with the actual exercise

00:29:32.329 --> 00:29:36.143
and you keep iterating on it
until you have a gem of a video

00:29:36.143 --> 00:29:37.579
and you can even have
multiple people's videos

00:29:37.579 --> 00:29:39.114
and see what's better
for different people.

00:29:39.114 --> 00:29:40.829
This all exists in Netflix.

00:29:40.829 --> 00:29:44.843
There's no reason why it
shouldn't exist in education.

00:29:47.986 --> 00:29:49.526
This right here is the big picture.

00:29:49.526 --> 00:29:52.255
I'm talking about a virtual
school for the world.

00:29:52.255 --> 00:29:57.293
This is what I think it's going
to be and I'm open to any ideas

00:29:57.293 --> 00:30:01.128
or any nuance parts of it, but
you have your video library.

00:30:01.128 --> 00:30:03.673
That's the low-hanging fruit, it's
the first line of instruction,

00:30:03.673 --> 00:30:05.211
you can pause it and repeat it.

00:30:05.211 --> 00:30:08.677
One thing, I spoke to a journal
of higher education recently

00:30:08.677 --> 00:30:12.176
and sometimes I'm very diplomatic,
I don't rock too many boats,

00:30:12.176 --> 00:30:16.211
but I was in a quirky mood and I hadn't
eaten for a long time. (laughter)

00:30:16.211 --> 00:30:17.948
People who know my eating
habits, I often don't eat

00:30:17.948 --> 00:30:20.543
for long periods of time,
but I just went off.

00:30:20.543 --> 00:30:22.753
I was like, "I challenge you,"
because this is a journal

00:30:22.753 --> 00:30:24.588
read by professors and educators.

00:30:24.588 --> 00:30:28.878
I was like, "Why does a 300 person
lecture even exist anymore?"

00:30:28.878 --> 00:30:32.212
In what way, just tell me
one way that that is better

00:30:32.212 --> 00:30:33.878
than on-demand video.

00:30:33.878 --> 00:30:36.267
I'm happy for any of you all to -

00:30:36.267 --> 00:30:40.105
It's this broadcast
lecture to a room of people

00:30:40.105 --> 00:30:42.006
in a certain amount of time
that's 90 minutes long,

00:30:42.006 --> 00:30:44.961
people have gaps, and the
professor sees blank faces.

00:30:44.961 --> 00:30:46.461
It's just this all around -

00:30:46.461 --> 00:30:47.847
I think the only reason it exists

00:30:47.847 --> 00:30:50.017
is because people associate it
with the college experience.

00:30:50.017 --> 00:30:53.684
People expect when I pay 30
or $40,000, I should get this.

00:30:53.684 --> 00:30:55.988
That's the only, in my
mind, why it exists.

00:30:55.988 --> 00:30:58.211
With on-demand video you
can pause, repeat it.

00:30:58.211 --> 00:31:03.095
The producer can get data on
what's working, what's not.

00:31:03.095 --> 00:31:05.543
You can get your best professors
to produce the best content

00:31:05.543 --> 00:31:07.378
and keep iterating it,
making it better and better.

00:31:07.378 --> 00:31:08.570
People can fill in their gaps.

00:31:08.570 --> 00:31:10.401
That's what the video library's all about.

00:31:10.401 --> 00:31:12.404
Then you have the web applications.

00:31:12.404 --> 00:31:14.368
You saw one of them, but
there's actually another one.

00:31:14.368 --> 00:31:15.951
There's some gentlemen
in the back of the room

00:31:15.951 --> 00:31:19.035
who started working on it.

00:31:19.035 --> 00:31:20.618
There's a whole suite of web
applications you can build

00:31:20.618 --> 00:31:22.285
for allowing people to
learn at their own pace.

00:31:22.285 --> 00:31:24.368
What you saw was for math.

00:31:24.368 --> 00:31:25.607
We're working on something.

00:31:25.607 --> 00:31:28.522
I'd be happy to talk about
it if you're all curious

00:31:28.522 --> 00:31:32.357
for more fact-based knowledge.

00:31:32.357 --> 00:31:35.107
Learning american history or
geography, things like that.

00:31:35.107 --> 00:31:37.329
You can even have web
applications for peer assessment,

00:31:37.329 --> 00:31:39.097
for creative writing, all sorts of things.

00:31:39.097 --> 00:31:40.606
When you actually compose things
for other people to review,

00:31:40.606 --> 00:31:42.801
it becomes a whole other
level, whole other game

00:31:42.801 --> 00:31:44.570
than when you're writing
something for a teacher to mark up

00:31:44.570 --> 00:31:47.805
and say you're a B+
and then throw it away.

00:31:47.805 --> 00:31:50.189
There's a whole suite of web
applications you can build

00:31:50.189 --> 00:31:51.976
and then on top of that
you use all of that data

00:31:51.976 --> 00:31:54.147
to actually facilitate
peer-to-peer interactions.

00:31:54.147 --> 00:31:56.149
I hinted that in the classroom,
but there's no reason why

00:31:56.149 --> 00:31:58.187
it just has to be
limited to the classroom.

00:31:58.187 --> 00:31:59.819
If I'm having trouble
with quantum mechanics

00:31:59.819 --> 00:32:01.988
and the best instructor for
quantum mechanics is in Mexico City

00:32:01.988 --> 00:32:05.322
and we're both free at
4:00 PM eastern time,

00:32:05.322 --> 00:32:07.522
no reason that we can't
set up an interaction

00:32:07.522 --> 00:32:09.939
with a pen tablet, the way I used
to do it with my cousin Nadia

00:32:09.939 --> 00:32:12.964
and have an interaction, even
better record that interaction,

00:32:12.964 --> 00:32:14.691
so that other people in
the future can use it.

00:32:14.691 --> 00:32:16.439
I rate them based on how they were,

00:32:16.439 --> 00:32:18.010
they can even rate me on
how I was as a student

00:32:18.010 --> 00:32:20.241
and the system knows what I did
before and after that interaction.

00:32:20.241 --> 00:32:23.410
It actually knows whether it
was a statistically significant

00:32:23.410 --> 00:32:25.492
intervention in some way.

00:32:25.492 --> 00:32:27.879
This is the big picture and you
can just keep getting the data

00:32:27.879 --> 00:32:30.772
and iterating and iterating and iterating
it to make it a better solution.

00:32:30.772 --> 00:32:35.653
That's the master plan. (laughter)

00:32:35.653 --> 00:32:37.357
Any questions?

00:32:37.357 --> 00:32:38.439
Yeah.

00:32:38.439 --> 00:32:40.424
Audience Member: I know
you've got this initial focus

00:32:40.424 --> 00:32:43.107
of K through 12 and math and whatnot.

00:32:43.107 --> 00:32:44.829
Audience Member: Sorry, we
can't hear the question.

00:32:44.829 --> 00:32:46.522
Audience Member: Okay,
one of the things you said

00:32:46.522 --> 00:32:49.105
really struck me as an
educator, which is your comment

00:32:49.105 --> 00:32:52.105
about everyone should be
forced to be an A student.

00:32:52.105 --> 00:32:55.522
If you think about this is
a (unintelligible) exercise

00:32:55.522 --> 00:32:59.343
with a lot of unwilling institutions
trying to get them to change.

00:32:59.343 --> 00:33:03.106
It seems to me that this
idea, just this one idea

00:33:03.106 --> 00:33:06.718
would be very powerful to take
into professional certification,

00:33:06.718 --> 00:33:10.689
say nursing degrees, where
you're not going to be a nurse

00:33:10.689 --> 00:33:14.060
until you achieve this level
of competency on the exam.

00:33:14.060 --> 00:33:17.464
Take a profession, where this idea

00:33:17.464 --> 00:33:19.164
that everybody does
have to be an A student

00:33:19.164 --> 00:33:24.303
in order to have a career and
get them to buy into this model

00:33:24.303 --> 00:33:26.803
and maybe get the resources
from that sort of problem

00:33:26.803 --> 00:33:31.022
or that sort of field
to test these ideas out

00:33:31.022 --> 00:33:34.814
and to show how they work or they
find implementation or whatever.

00:33:34.814 --> 00:33:38.105
Sal: I think it exists in
professional development,

00:33:38.105 --> 00:33:39.483
because people say,
"Look, if you're a nurse

00:33:39.483 --> 00:33:41.154
"and you don't know this,
people are going to die,"

00:33:41.154 --> 00:33:45.707
so they do enforce that
with doctors, nurses, and -

00:33:45.707 --> 00:33:47.684
That exists, but it isn't -

00:33:47.684 --> 00:33:53.314
We could do studies, but I
think it's almost intuitive

00:33:53.314 --> 00:33:54.858
that if you go back to -

00:33:54.858 --> 00:33:58.145
Someone that has real mastery of algebra

00:33:58.145 --> 00:34:00.931
is going to be way more
powerful than someone

00:34:00.931 --> 00:34:03.478
who has B- student level of understanding

00:34:03.478 --> 00:34:05.570
of algebra through differential equations.

00:34:05.570 --> 00:34:07.184
They're never going to be
able to apply any of it,

00:34:07.184 --> 00:34:08.124
as opposed to -

00:34:08.124 --> 00:34:10.641
I've worked at - When I was
working at a hedge fund,

00:34:10.641 --> 00:34:14.040
there was once a CFO who said -

00:34:14.040 --> 00:34:16.125
I was like, "What's your
incremental gross margin?"

00:34:16.125 --> 00:34:16.781
He's like, "Oh, we don't divulge that."

00:34:16.781 --> 00:34:19.063
I was like, "You just gave it to me.

00:34:19.063 --> 00:34:21.562
"You told me your gross
profit in two periods

00:34:21.562 --> 00:34:23.893
"and how many units you sold
in two periods (laughter)

00:34:23.893 --> 00:34:24.977
"That's your -

00:34:24.977 --> 00:34:27.589
Everyone in the room was like, "Oh my God,

00:34:27.589 --> 00:34:29.893
"this is some kind of
rocket science," (laughter)

00:34:29.893 --> 00:34:34.562
That is algebra one, that is
algebra one, and no one in the room.

00:34:34.562 --> 00:34:38.144
There are MBAs, there were PhDs
in the room, very smart people,

00:34:38.144 --> 00:34:40.893
but no one could recognize
