00:34:40.893 --> 00:34:43.205
and these are the successful
people in our education system.

00:34:43.205 --> 00:34:45.040
People need to -

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:49.412
If we had real mastery of algebra,
the world would be a different place.

00:34:49.412 --> 00:34:50.992
All the calculus and
all of that other stuff

00:34:50.992 --> 00:34:54.453
would just be for fun, but it's not -

00:34:54.453 --> 00:34:57.501
I don't even think it has to be tested.

00:34:57.501 --> 00:34:59.861
If people really understood algebra,

00:34:59.861 --> 00:35:01.170
that's going to be way better

00:35:01.170 --> 00:35:03.027
than people halfway understanding algebra

00:35:03.027 --> 00:35:06.029
and then moving on to other things.

00:35:06.029 --> 00:35:07.310
Yeah?

00:35:07.310 --> 00:35:08.943
Audience Member: A question about
the peer-to-peer interaction.

00:35:08.943 --> 00:35:11.579
Do you see that happening now, actually?

00:35:11.579 --> 00:35:14.718
If you have 16 million views on
YouTube, I imagine there's comments.

00:35:14.718 --> 00:35:18.420
Is there comment moderation happening?

00:35:18.420 --> 00:35:20.019
Sal: You all can go home and look.

00:35:20.019 --> 00:35:23.858
Some of the debates or
even some of the commentary

00:35:23.858 --> 00:35:25.251
on the YouTube videos
are like what teachers

00:35:25.251 --> 00:35:27.195
would dream of having in their classroom.

00:35:27.195 --> 00:35:28.894
Someone says, "Hey,
this was a great video,

00:35:28.894 --> 00:35:32.146
"but I don't quite get what
Sal did at minute 2:34,"

00:35:32.146 --> 00:35:33.561
and there's a little link in
YouTube you can go right back

00:35:33.561 --> 00:35:35.396
to that little point in the video.

00:35:35.396 --> 00:35:37.561
Then other people will
comment on it and say,

00:35:37.561 --> 00:35:39.228
"Oh, you just have to
watch that other video

00:35:39.228 --> 00:35:42.175
"and he explains that in depth," or,
"Here's another page you can watch,"

00:35:42.175 --> 00:35:44.479
or they'll actually just
explain it right there.

00:35:44.479 --> 00:35:46.063
This is just on a simple message board.

00:35:46.063 --> 00:35:50.121
It definitely already exists
and it's literally just -

00:35:50.121 --> 00:35:54.170
I get at least five emails a day
asking for a better community

00:35:54.170 --> 00:35:57.296
to tap into this and I've just
been waiting to do it right.

00:35:57.296 --> 00:36:01.081
It's there and people
love to help each other

00:36:01.081 --> 00:36:04.292
and they just don't have a
good way of doing it right now.

00:36:04.914 --> 00:36:07.267
Audience Member: I have children in
the first grade and fourth grade.

00:36:07.267 --> 00:36:10.468
What would you suggest I
do with them with this?

00:36:10.468 --> 00:36:11.566
Sal: First through fourth?

00:36:11.566 --> 00:36:14.409
Audience Member: First and fourth.

00:36:14.409 --> 00:36:15.575
Sal: This is not scientific.

00:36:15.575 --> 00:36:18.438
I've tried out the app
with different aged kids.

00:36:18.438 --> 00:36:23.556
The 1+1, it is 1+1 but it doesn't
have dancing bears. (laughter)

00:36:23.556 --> 00:36:25.253
I hope to eventually have dancing -

00:36:25.253 --> 00:36:29.603
Everyone likes dancing
(laughter) A Kindergartner.

00:36:29.603 --> 00:36:31.224
I found Kindergarten -

00:36:31.224 --> 00:36:34.430
I've seen some precocious second
or third graders get into it.

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:36.061
They don't need the
dancing bears and the music

00:36:36.061 --> 00:36:37.856
and all of that type of thing.

00:36:37.856 --> 00:36:42.381
Your fourth grader, I think,
could be ready for this.

00:36:42.381 --> 00:36:45.572
The videos I've seen very
young kids like them.

00:36:45.572 --> 00:36:46.840
They like the -

00:36:46.840 --> 00:36:47.604
I don't know what they like about it.

00:36:47.604 --> 00:36:50.939
They like the black
background and the colors.

00:36:50.939 --> 00:36:52.815
They respond to the videos.

00:36:52.815 --> 00:36:55.354
I've seen three or four year
olds, it holds their attention.

00:36:55.354 --> 00:36:57.869
I don't know if they're
retaining anything. (laughter)

00:36:57.869 --> 00:37:01.767
You might want to start with the
videos for your younger student,

00:37:01.767 --> 00:37:04.644
but the fourth grader, I
think, is ready for the app.

00:37:04.644 --> 00:37:06.766
Audience Member: The younger kid
goes straight to the YouTube.

00:37:06.766 --> 00:37:10.562
Sal: Yeah, I think so, and you
might want to watch it with them.

00:37:10.562 --> 00:37:12.184
Some people have told me that
they watch a couple of videos

00:37:12.184 --> 00:37:17.268
at night with their kid and it's in
place of a bedtime story. (laughter)

00:37:17.268 --> 00:37:19.171
Why not?

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:22.037
Audience Member: Are your
videos in your system

00:37:22.073 --> 00:37:24.988
a little too big for one laptop per child?

00:37:24.988 --> 00:37:26.045
Audience Member: What's the question?

00:37:26.045 --> 00:37:27.322
Sal: The question is your
video and your system

00:37:27.322 --> 00:37:30.566
a little too big for one laptop per child?

00:37:30.566 --> 00:37:31.682
I guess there's a couple of -

00:37:31.682 --> 00:37:34.182
In terms of ...

00:37:34.182 --> 00:37:35.905
Audience Member: Getting
any of that content to them,

00:37:35.905 --> 00:37:38.622
because right now I think they're
just doing textbook format, right?

00:37:38.622 --> 00:37:40.691
Sal: Yeah, so the
question is, is it too big

00:37:40.691 --> 00:37:44.740
for getting the content
into one laptop per child?

00:37:44.740 --> 00:37:46.071
The easy answer is no.

00:37:46.071 --> 00:37:48.863
When I first saw one laptop per child,

00:37:48.863 --> 00:37:50.905
this is before Khan Academy
was really well thought out,

00:37:50.905 --> 00:37:53.100
I was like, "What are they going to
do on that one laptop per child?"

00:37:53.100 --> 00:37:55.941
There's examples of people
using it for lights and things

00:37:55.941 --> 00:38:01.153
as opposed to for a computer.

00:38:01.153 --> 00:38:05.615
I think it could be used
tomorrow on one laptop per child.

00:38:05.615 --> 00:38:07.490
Audience Member: But do
they have enough drive space

00:38:07.490 --> 00:38:08.613
and things like that?

00:38:08.613 --> 00:38:13.362
A lot of them don't have
network connectivity.

00:38:13.362 --> 00:38:16.432
Sal: The raw videos, they're
going to be on iTunes U soon,

00:38:16.432 --> 00:38:18.267
so I just talked to the Apple
people and I handed them the disk

00:38:18.267 --> 00:38:22.716
that had all the raw
videos and it was 40 gigs.

00:38:22.716 --> 00:38:26.967
I think if you took the
Flash versions, it's 14 gigs.

00:38:26.967 --> 00:38:28.633
I don't know how big the
hard drives are, though,

00:38:28.633 --> 00:38:31.780
but soon they're going to be
able to store all of the -

00:38:31.780 --> 00:38:33.749
Audience Member: It's actually
something you should look into,

00:38:33.749 --> 00:38:35.084
because that's a big deal, right?

00:38:35.084 --> 00:38:35.967
Sal: I would love to.

00:38:35.967 --> 00:38:41.004
If they called me up, I'd
say, "Yeah." (laughter)

00:38:41.004 --> 00:38:42.506
I'd love to, I'd love to.

00:38:42.506 --> 00:38:47.067
We can have another talk about -

00:38:47.067 --> 00:38:51.338
I'm talking to a couple of foundations.

00:38:51.338 --> 00:38:53.999
One laptop per child would be
awesome if there's the resources,

00:38:53.999 --> 00:38:56.326
but you don't necessarily
need one laptop per child.

00:38:56.326 --> 00:39:00.084
Get some $200 refurbished
PC, put it in the village.

00:39:00.084 --> 00:39:01.835
Now, all of a sudden, you can
have asynchronous learning,

00:39:01.835 --> 00:39:03.302
which is what these village kids need,

00:39:03.302 --> 00:39:05.138
because they have to
take off for the harvest,

00:39:05.138 --> 00:39:06.409
they have a whole spectrum.

00:39:06.409 --> 00:39:07.475
Some of them can't read, some of them have

00:39:07.475 --> 00:39:10.667
pretty reasonable proficiency.

00:39:10.667 --> 00:39:16.283
That $200 refurbished PC,
instead of being one per student,

00:39:16.283 --> 00:39:19.149
you have 20 students
per day working on it,

00:39:19.149 --> 00:39:21.584
each half an hour a day,
doing this type of thing,

00:39:21.584 --> 00:39:23.792
and then as a foundation, for
the first time in the history

00:39:23.792 --> 00:39:25.237
of philanthropic giving,
you actually have real data

00:39:25.237 --> 00:39:28.327
on what's happening in real
time on the actual utilization

00:39:28.327 --> 00:39:31.084
on your assets, where students
are, how they're performing

00:39:31.084 --> 00:39:34.500
and in terms of the actual
cost, it's a $200 PC

00:39:34.500 --> 00:39:36.834
that'll last four years,
so it's $50 a year

00:39:36.834 --> 00:39:38.036
and you're educating 20 students.

00:39:38.036 --> 00:39:40.750
That's $2.50 per student
per year for an education,

00:39:40.750 --> 00:39:42.667
which is competitive with
anywhere in the third world.

00:39:42.667 --> 00:39:43.916
It's cheaper than pencil and paper.

00:39:43.916 --> 00:39:47.079
I think that's what should be the model,

00:39:47.079 --> 00:39:50.218
but if they get a laptop
that's even better.

00:39:50.218 --> 00:39:51.501
Oh, in the back, yeah.

00:39:51.501 --> 00:39:52.452
Audience Member: I think you said you do

00:39:52.452 --> 00:39:55.003
all the video and lectures yourself.

00:39:55.003 --> 00:39:59.014
How long does it take you
to put together a module?

00:39:59.014 --> 00:40:07.641
There's some topic areas surely you
don't know all of it. (laughter)

00:40:07.641 --> 00:40:11.099
Sal: A video, if it's a work -

00:40:11.099 --> 00:40:13.598
There's probably people emailing
me right now some algebra.

00:40:13.598 --> 00:40:16.431
I think I may really be doing
some kid's homework for them.

00:40:16.431 --> 00:40:19.150
Those type of things where
it's just an algebra problem,

00:40:19.150 --> 00:40:22.655
someone emails it to me, I haven't
done that exact problem before,

00:40:22.655 --> 00:40:26.493
let me just do it, that's
the ten minutes on the video,

00:40:26.493 --> 00:40:29.062
plus five minutes to upload,
it's a very small amount of time.

00:40:29.062 --> 00:40:31.932
If you saw that first screen, I've
started doing world history videos.

00:40:31.932 --> 00:40:34.833
Those take a lot of -

00:40:34.833 --> 00:40:37.898
Audience Member: What
do you mean by a lot?

00:40:37.898 --> 00:40:40.155
Sal: When I started on
the French Revolution,

00:40:40.155 --> 00:40:44.003
I spent a week doing nothing but
reading on the French Revolution.

00:40:44.003 --> 00:40:47.435
I literally just took time off and I
steeped myself in the French Revolution.

00:40:47.435 --> 00:40:49.203
I think we've all found this
when we were going to school

00:40:49.203 --> 00:40:50.984
is that when you're in
the midst of a class,

00:40:50.984 --> 00:40:54.150
you really are an expert for
that short period of time

00:40:54.150 --> 00:41:01.617
until the exam you are an expert,
but then it all goes away. (laughter)

00:41:01.617 --> 00:41:02.650
For that short period
of time, you can talk

00:41:02.650 --> 00:41:03.733
to any academic anywhere in the world

00:41:03.733 --> 00:41:06.688
and you know all of the details
and the nuances and everything.

00:41:06.688 --> 00:41:09.928
About a week of studying
and it's fun studying.

00:41:09.928 --> 00:41:13.150
It's not for an exam, it's for me
and I get to make YouTube videos.

00:41:13.150 --> 00:41:16.432
I'll do that and then I'll
start making the videos

00:41:16.432 --> 00:41:19.434
and then I can probably produce
two or three videos a day.

00:41:19.434 --> 00:41:22.136
Once I have the big picture and
I understand the major pieces

00:41:22.136 --> 00:41:23.869
and I have a sense of -

00:41:23.869 --> 00:41:27.008
If you watch those videos, I
cut and paste a bunch of images

00:41:27.008 --> 00:41:30.510
and maps from Wikipedia
and I just explain them.

00:41:30.510 --> 00:41:33.547
I'm a big map person, so I do that.

00:41:33.547 --> 00:41:34.900
In the back?

00:41:34.900 --> 00:41:36.785
Audience Member: Is the software
that you use to do things

00:41:36.785 --> 00:41:39.317
like draw perfectly straight
lines or doing a ratio

00:41:39.317 --> 00:41:41.982
something you can buy off
the shelf (unintelligible)

00:41:41.982 --> 00:41:43.149
or did you design that all yourself?

00:41:43.149 --> 00:41:45.571
Sal: No, some people have
offered to pay for it,

00:41:45.571 --> 00:41:47.794
but I didn't build any software.

00:41:47.794 --> 00:41:54.102
Actually, all I use is I started
off using Microsoft Paint.

00:41:54.102 --> 00:41:57.315
I made the background
black and I used this thing

00:41:57.315 --> 00:42:00.148
called Screen Video Recorder,
too, which is this shareware,

00:42:00.148 --> 00:42:03.776
freeware, or $20 screen capture software.

00:42:03.776 --> 00:42:07.312
That's what I started the first
500 videos were done like that.

00:42:07.312 --> 00:42:09.394
Then someone just sent
me a Camtasia license.

00:42:09.394 --> 00:42:12.576
They're like, "This is great,
we need to (unintelligible).

00:42:12.576 --> 00:42:15.126
"You need a better screen capture."

00:42:15.126 --> 00:42:17.727
So I started using Camtasia and
then I used Smooth Draw, too,

00:42:17.727 --> 00:42:21.632
which is pressure sensitive,
so it actually looks like
I'm writing with a pen,

00:42:21.632 --> 00:42:25.103
as opposed to Microsoft Paint,
but you could get set up

00:42:25.103 --> 00:42:27.991
for $200 at home with exactly what I have.

00:42:27.991 --> 00:42:30.074
It's all found stuff.

00:42:30.074 --> 00:42:31.242
There's probably better stuff out there.

00:42:31.242 --> 00:42:33.326
What I'm using right now, I
can't draw a straight line.

00:42:33.326 --> 00:42:37.556
With Microsoft Paint I could,
because it had the line tool.

00:42:37.556 --> 00:42:40.190
Audience Member: In line with your
idea of this as entertainment,

00:42:40.190 --> 00:42:45.089
so replacing bedtime stories, I
think there's a niche for retirees.

00:42:45.089 --> 00:42:47.941
I know any number of people
who, first thing in the morning,

00:42:47.941 --> 00:42:50.191
do three crosswords and a sudoku.

00:42:50.191 --> 00:42:50.947
Sal: Exactly.

00:42:50.947 --> 00:42:54.966
Audience Member: (unintelligible)

00:42:54.966 --> 00:43:00.740
Sal: (unintelligible)

00:43:00.740 --> 00:43:06.715
My mother in law
(unintelligible) (laughter)

00:43:06.715 --> 00:43:11.047
I have gotten letters from retirees saying

00:43:11.047 --> 00:43:14.012
that they started doing
it instead of sudoku

00:43:14.012 --> 00:43:18.432
and other than keeping them sharp,

00:43:18.432 --> 00:43:19.990
they're not connecting
with their grandkids.

00:43:19.990 --> 00:43:21.467
They're becoming the grandkids' tutor

00:43:21.467 --> 00:43:22.656
and this is a whole level of connection

00:43:22.656 --> 00:43:24.870
that they couldn't have
before, so there is something.

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:29.969
Not the retirees, there's a
lot of homeschooling parents -

00:43:29.969 --> 00:43:31.719
I think there's a lot of
homeschoolers who are doing great

00:43:31.719 --> 00:43:34.678
until about algebra and then
they're like, "What do I do next?"

00:43:34.678 --> 00:43:37.110
This is helping them out.

00:43:37.110 --> 00:43:39.552
There's a lot of people who surprise me.

00:43:39.552 --> 00:43:41.410
There's a lot of military
people who are actually my age

00:43:41.410 --> 00:43:43.645
who are going back to college.

00:43:43.645 --> 00:43:45.647
If you think about it,
if you're in your mid-30s

00:43:45.647 --> 00:43:48.230
and you want to go back to college,

00:43:48.230 --> 00:43:49.842
and the first thing you're going
to see when you go to college

00:43:49.842 --> 00:43:51.770
is college algebra and (unintelligible)

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:55.269
There is nothing out there for you.

00:43:55.269 --> 00:43:57.353
You're helpless and this is
the only thing that's out there

00:43:57.353 --> 00:44:00.103
and they're eternally thankful
that they could re-learn

00:44:00.103 --> 00:44:02.201
arithmetic and algebra
and all these things

00:44:02.201 --> 00:44:03.434
that they haven't seen for 20 years.

00:44:03.434 --> 00:44:05.317
It's surprising.

00:44:05.317 --> 00:44:07.102
Audience Member: I have an eighth grader

00:44:07.102 --> 00:44:13.067
and my question is, would you
say that the videos sometimes

00:44:13.067 --> 00:44:19.307
could replace going back to the
textbook when they get stuck, or -

00:44:19.307 --> 00:44:21.524
Sal: Yeah, so the question and this -

00:44:21.524 --> 00:44:23.092
Audience Member: Because the textbooks -

00:44:23.092 --> 00:44:26.139
Sal: Oh, don't get me started
about textbooks. (laughter)

00:44:26.139 --> 00:44:27.640
No, I will get started about textbooks.

00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:30.334
The question was, "I
have an eighth grader.

00:44:30.334 --> 00:44:33.870
"Do you think the videos
can replace the textbook?"

00:44:33.870 --> 00:44:36.057
Let's think about what a textbook is.

00:44:36.057 --> 00:44:37.224
There's two things in a textbook.

00:44:37.224 --> 00:44:41.890
There's something that claims
to be some form of explanation,

00:44:41.890 --> 00:44:45.884
two pages of text on something,
and then it's exercises.

00:44:45.884 --> 00:44:50.017
There's 50 problems (unintelligible).

00:44:50.017 --> 00:44:52.300
I guarantee you on-demand
video, whether it's Khan Academy

00:44:52.300 --> 00:44:55.524
or anybody, is going to
be better than that prose

00:44:55.524 --> 00:44:59.217
or whatever you want to call it,
that's trying to explain the concept

00:44:59.217 --> 00:45:01.799
and it's usually explained
more for peer-review,

00:45:01.799 --> 00:45:03.497
more for the other
textbook authors saying,

00:45:03.497 --> 00:45:05.933
"Oh yes, he did it
rigorously, that's excellent,"

00:45:05.933 --> 00:45:09.201
as opposed for the
eighth grader who wants -

00:45:09.201 --> 00:45:10.336
Audience Member: (unintelligible)

00:45:10.336 --> 00:45:14.340
Sal: Exactly, I think there's
a small subset of people

00:45:14.340 --> 00:45:16.843
who could actually read a textbook
and that's what a lot of us

00:45:16.843 --> 00:45:18.967
would probably get where
we got, because we could

00:45:18.967 --> 00:45:21.014
actually consume that
information, but most people -

00:45:21.014 --> 00:45:23.349
On-demand video is better than that

00:45:23.349 --> 00:45:25.586
and from an exercise point of view,

00:45:25.586 --> 00:45:28.550
the textbook company doesn't know
who's doing what exercise when,

00:45:28.550 --> 00:45:30.489
who's watching what, what's
actually being effective.

00:45:30.489 --> 00:45:31.485
They're not getting real-time data.

00:45:31.485 --> 00:45:32.325
That stuff I showed -

00:45:32.325 --> 00:45:34.717
You can argue what the
modules should look like,

00:45:34.717 --> 00:45:37.052
but something like that is
going to be infinitely better,

00:45:37.052 --> 00:45:39.166
especially if you can tweak it
and get data on what's working,

00:45:39.166 --> 00:45:40.217
what are people using.

00:45:40.217 --> 00:45:41.549
For all we know, textbook publishers,

00:45:41.549 --> 00:45:44.669
half of those problems are
never touched by anybody.

00:45:44.669 --> 00:45:46.037
They're in there and
kids are getting hernias

00:45:46.037 --> 00:45:48.800
carrying those problems
around and it's a -

00:45:48.800 --> 00:45:54.119
The answer's yes, I think that textbooks
need to go, on a lot of levels.

00:45:54.119 --> 00:45:56.056
Audience Member: So for world history,

00:45:56.056 --> 00:45:58.593
what kind of problems do you put out there

00:45:58.593 --> 00:46:00.528
so you can make your assessment?

00:46:00.528 --> 00:46:01.764
Sal: The question is for world history

00:46:01.764 --> 00:46:04.704
what kind of problems
can you put out there?

00:46:04.704 --> 00:46:07.204
What I showed you, those modules,
that's good for something

00:46:07.204 --> 00:46:09.704
that can be templatized, that you can map.

00:46:09.704 --> 00:46:13.620
You can even do some physics problems
like that, the core problems.

00:46:13.620 --> 00:46:15.876
You could do some types of
chemistry, maybe genetics,

00:46:15.876 --> 00:46:18.873
but what about the
causes of the Civil War.

00:46:18.873 --> 00:46:22.764
Audience Member: Not just that,
