I literally would record
it and put up. (laughter)

00:58:05.816 --> 00:58:08.621
There's actually one or two videos
where I'm answering telemarketer calls.

00:58:08.621 --> 00:58:10.290
(laughter) I didn't care.

00:58:10.290 --> 00:58:11.234
Why re-record it?

00:58:11.234 --> 00:58:12.193
It's for Nadia.

00:58:12.193 --> 00:58:14.961
This is free (unintelligible).

00:58:14.961 --> 00:58:16.294
That's another takeaway.

00:58:16.294 --> 00:58:20.225
People like that
informality, they like that -

00:58:20.225 --> 00:58:21.766
I make mistakes.

00:58:21.766 --> 00:58:24.560
I would say one out of every
12 videos I make on arithmetic,

00:58:24.560 --> 00:58:27.395
I forget a negative number
or I forget a negative sign

00:58:27.395 --> 00:58:30.016
or I say 16-8 is 5.

00:58:30.016 --> 00:58:34.016
I do something bizarre and people
really like that. (laughter)

00:58:34.016 --> 00:58:36.598
Or I start a problem and go
around the wrong path first

00:58:36.598 --> 00:58:39.046
and I say, "Oh wait, that's not right."

00:58:39.046 --> 00:58:42.213
I've gotten positive feedback on
those things because you never see it.

00:58:42.213 --> 00:58:45.153
When you go to a class, the
teacher they have the script,

00:58:45.153 --> 00:58:47.546
they've done that problem 20
times and they just do it perfect.

00:58:47.546 --> 00:58:51.595
You're an idiot if you didn't
see this, obvious steps,

00:58:51.595 --> 00:58:53.695
but when you see someone who
kind of knows what they're doing,

00:58:53.695 --> 00:58:55.831
they follow their intuition in
one direction, it was wrong,

00:58:55.831 --> 00:58:59.068
that's okay, that's the art of
mathematics, of solving a problem.

00:58:59.068 --> 00:59:02.242
Then you go down a complete other path.

00:59:02.242 --> 00:59:05.409
I try now that it's
getting more notoriety,

00:59:05.409 --> 00:59:07.177
I feel like, "Oh my God, so many
people are going to watch this video,

00:59:07.177 --> 00:59:10.807
"let me re-do it," but I find
the more I think that way

00:59:10.807 --> 00:59:14.061
it hurts the quality of the video.

00:59:14.061 --> 00:59:15.556
Audience Member: Does Kaplan or any

00:59:15.556 --> 00:59:18.390
of the other paid for online
services, Phoenix University,

00:59:18.390 --> 00:59:22.561
do any of them view you as a
competitive threat, being free?

00:59:22.561 --> 00:59:28.305
Sal: They should. (laughter)

00:59:28.305 --> 00:59:30.721
I've actually spoke to the
research group at Apollo Group,

00:59:30.721 --> 00:59:33.943
which is the parent company
for the University of Phoenix.

00:59:33.943 --> 00:59:36.442
I think they're aware of it now.

00:59:36.442 --> 00:59:38.610
I've talked to Princeton
Review about potentially -

00:59:38.610 --> 00:59:39.580
Because I would like to do something

00:59:39.580 --> 00:59:42.137
with their materials and all of that.

00:59:42.137 --> 00:59:44.971
In any of these groups,
even textbook publishers,

00:59:44.971 --> 00:59:49.590
I've talked to a few, there's a group
that's very insecure about everything,

00:59:49.590 --> 00:59:53.388
but there's another view that's
like, "Look, this is out there

00:59:53.388 --> 00:59:55.532
"and this could even
empower your instruction."

00:59:55.532 --> 00:59:57.994
If I do all the SAT
problems out of your book,

00:59:57.994 --> 01:00:00.305
hopefully you'll donate
to me and I can do them,

01:00:00.305 --> 01:00:01.722
that's not going to
prevent people from taking

01:00:01.722 --> 01:00:03.137
your Princeton Review course.

01:00:03.137 --> 01:00:04.888
It's going to make your time
in your Princeton Review course

01:00:04.888 --> 01:00:07.875
way more productive, because the
kids will have done the problems,

01:00:07.875 --> 01:00:10.411
get all their questions
answered by this Sal guy

01:00:10.411 --> 01:00:11.913
and then they can have
this one-on-one interaction

01:00:11.913 --> 01:00:17.102
with the guy you're paying to teach.

01:00:17.102 --> 01:00:19.628
I've talked to Princeton
Review and the Apollo Group

01:00:19.628 --> 01:00:22.509
who definitely believe that, but
then they have to fight the inertia

01:00:22.509 --> 01:00:27.710
of we have this billion dollar
franchise, we can't mess it up.

01:00:27.710 --> 01:00:29.042
Once they really view me as a competitor,

01:00:29.042 --> 01:00:32.562
then I'll start getting
security. (laughter)

01:00:32.562 --> 01:00:34.863
Audience Member: Hi, I'm
wondering if you can speak

01:00:34.863 --> 01:00:38.569
on anything more to how you devised
the content for your videos.

01:00:38.569 --> 01:00:41.670
Are you looking at textbooks
and here's the order of content,

01:00:41.670 --> 01:00:43.779
because you're not a fan of textbooks.

01:00:43.779 --> 01:00:47.694
I'm wondering if there's a
potential to reconceptualize

01:00:47.694 --> 01:00:50.029
the way knowledge is
organized to begin with,

01:00:50.029 --> 01:00:53.114
because I was lucky, I could
follow textbooks very well,

01:00:53.114 --> 01:00:58.278
but our natural curiosities
don't follow (unintelligible).

01:00:58.278 --> 01:01:01.559
Early childhood educators are
very often going to have that.

01:01:01.559 --> 01:01:04.028
You go to class
(unintelligible) and it's killed

01:01:04.028 --> 01:01:06.729
many children's natural curiosities.

01:01:06.729 --> 01:01:09.613
How can you link the
basics that you're teaching

01:01:09.613 --> 01:01:12.186
to the real world questions that we have?

01:01:12.186 --> 01:01:16.528
(unintelligible)

01:01:16.528 --> 01:01:18.321
Sal: The question is how
do I build the curriculum?

01:01:18.321 --> 01:01:21.530
How do I decide what to cover,
given that I'm not a fan -

01:01:21.530 --> 01:01:23.813
I'm not a fan of a textbook
as a primary learning source

01:01:23.813 --> 01:01:25.091
for someone who's -

01:01:25.091 --> 01:01:27.496
I do look at textbooks.

01:01:27.496 --> 01:01:32.723
I don't go straight, section 12-1, next
lecture, section 12-2, next lecture.

01:01:32.723 --> 01:01:33.943
Actually, there's a textbook publisher

01:01:33.943 --> 01:01:35.993
who wanted me to do videos for their book

01:01:35.993 --> 01:01:40.332
and they said, "I want you to do
exactly this concept on this video."

01:01:40.332 --> 01:01:43.779
I looked at that concept, I was like,
"There's no way I can get myself

01:01:43.779 --> 01:01:45.403
- It would be so boring.

01:01:45.403 --> 01:01:47.695
It would be just so mundane it
would just kill all my credibility

01:01:47.695 --> 01:01:49.973
if I were to do a video on that.

01:01:49.973 --> 01:01:52.364
My thing is I try to get the big picture

01:01:52.364 --> 01:01:53.505
(unintelligible) with
the French Revolution.

01:01:53.505 --> 01:01:56.038
Spend some time, mull over it, and
then once you have the big picture,

01:01:56.038 --> 01:02:00.288
then try to take the nuggets that
will build you the big picture.

01:02:00.288 --> 01:02:02.979
Then maybe use the
textbook or something else

01:02:02.979 --> 01:02:04.372
just to make sure you're comprehenseive.

01:02:04.372 --> 01:02:06.747
The kid's going to see
everything that they might face

01:02:06.747 --> 01:02:08.316
when they take an assessment.

01:02:08.316 --> 01:02:12.871
I use a ton of Wikipedia, I use textbooks,

01:02:12.871 --> 01:02:17.827
I use other open
courseware sometimes, to -

01:02:17.827 --> 01:02:19.893
A lot of stuff is hard to consume.

01:02:19.893 --> 01:02:21.619
You really have to be motivated to consume

01:02:21.619 --> 01:02:25.204
or already even have a foundation
to consume a lot of these things.

01:02:25.204 --> 01:02:27.399
I feel my value-added
is taking all of that

01:02:27.399 --> 01:02:31.840
and distilling it down
to something useful.

01:02:31.840 --> 01:02:46.821
Audience Member: In your model up there
you have a figure (unintelligible)

01:02:46.821 --> 01:02:54.288
How have you thought of looking
at environmental (unintelligible)

01:02:54.288 --> 01:02:57.536
Stress can be measured in
learning by somebody blinking or -

01:02:57.536 --> 01:03:03.237
(unintelligible)

01:03:03.237 --> 01:03:04.672
Sal: The question is right
now I'm just tracking

01:03:04.672 --> 01:03:06.620
when they're doing the problem,
how long it's taking them,

01:03:06.620 --> 01:03:08.454
what time of day they're doing it,
did they get it right or wrong,

01:03:08.454 --> 01:03:10.296
did they click the hint,
all that type of stuff,

01:03:10.296 --> 01:03:12.647
but there's this whole what
was their blood pressure

01:03:12.647 --> 01:03:14.113
while they were doing
the problem, (laughter)

01:03:14.113 --> 01:03:16.817
where did their eyes move,

01:03:16.817 --> 01:03:20.705
what is their cycles in
their brain doing on an EEG?

01:03:20.705 --> 01:03:22.491
I think that'd be awesome.

01:03:22.491 --> 01:03:25.786
You could do some biofeedback stuff.

01:03:25.786 --> 01:03:28.163
That's a whole frontier that I think is -

01:03:28.163 --> 01:03:29.802
Audience Member: The only
bad thing is you don't want

01:03:29.802 --> 01:03:33.620
to hook somebody up to
an EEG (unintelligible)

01:03:33.620 --> 01:03:40.037
Sal: (unintelligible) If it can be
done, try it out and see if it -

01:03:40.037 --> 01:03:41.900
I think that'd be awesome.

01:03:41.900 --> 01:03:44.015
Camerawoman: There's research
already in effective computing

01:03:44.015 --> 01:03:46.313
in Media Lab and Rosalind Picard.

01:03:46.313 --> 01:03:51.876
That's what (crosstalk)
She was my adviser.

01:03:51.876 --> 01:04:00.209
Then they do sweat measurement
and eye dilation (crosstalk)

01:04:00.209 --> 01:04:02.378
Sal: I think the fun thing about
this, what I view as the Khan Academy,

01:04:02.378 --> 01:04:04.097
right now it's very content focused.

01:04:04.097 --> 01:04:05.666
Everything I talked about was the videos

01:04:05.666 --> 01:04:07.961
and these modules and all of
that, but where I see it going

01:04:07.961 --> 01:04:10.570
is the content is really just seeding.

01:04:10.570 --> 01:04:12.840
In order to do all this data
stuff, you need the content,

01:04:12.840 --> 01:04:16.010
but once you have a critical mass of
content, then the data takes over.

01:04:16.010 --> 01:04:17.845
You can start doing some
really fascinating things

01:04:17.845 --> 01:04:21.378
with experiments that you
couldn't have done before

01:04:21.378 --> 01:04:25.287
and real-time learning and biofeedback
and all this other (unintelligible)

01:04:25.287 --> 01:04:28.323
I think that'd be awesome.

01:04:28.323 --> 01:04:29.655
Audience Member: In the
beginning of your talk

01:04:29.655 --> 01:04:35.831
you said your visitors to your
website surpass MIT (unintelligible)

01:04:35.831 --> 01:04:36.765
Is that true?

01:04:36.765 --> 01:04:39.099
Sal: I'll give you all my data.

01:04:39.099 --> 01:04:42.876
Audience Member: (unintelligible)

01:04:42.876 --> 01:04:47.575
Sal: How do I know that
it's past (unintelligible)

01:04:47.575 --> 01:04:49.508
Audience Member: (unintelligible)

01:04:49.508 --> 01:04:50.459
Sal: There's a couple things.

01:04:50.459 --> 01:04:51.959
There's an interesting thing about -

01:04:51.959 --> 01:04:55.293
Just on YouTube, which I think
is the primary consumption area

01:04:55.293 --> 01:04:59.209
for most open courseware,
it has passed up MIT.

01:04:59.209 --> 01:05:04.126
You can actually look at the cumulative
upload views on a daily basis

01:05:04.126 --> 01:05:07.094
and just measure the delta and you can see

01:05:07.094 --> 01:05:09.998
that Khan Academy's
getting about 60 or 70,000,

01:05:09.998 --> 01:05:12.265
MIT's getting about 30 to 40,000.

01:05:12.265 --> 01:05:17.103
I think next up is Berkeley's getting
15,000 or something like that.

01:05:17.103 --> 01:05:19.128
That's just on that.

01:05:19.128 --> 01:05:23.409
I don't have access to
MIT's actual weblogs.

01:05:23.409 --> 01:05:29.746
(unintelligible) Definitely on
the internet, I'm not 100% sure.

01:05:29.746 --> 01:05:32.190
Audience Member: It's
definitely a different audience.

01:05:32.190 --> 01:05:33.653
Sal: That's the other interesting thing.

01:05:33.653 --> 01:05:35.103
There's all this open courseware,

01:05:35.103 --> 01:05:37.925
people spend millions of
dollars putting cameras in,

01:05:37.925 --> 01:05:40.436
but Khan Academy's really only
the game in town for K through 12,

01:05:40.436 --> 01:05:42.762
which is where all the need is.

01:05:42.762 --> 01:05:44.631
It's not like I'm like, "Oh, MIT ...

01:05:44.631 --> 01:05:47.267
They're catering to us.

01:05:47.267 --> 01:05:51.186
If we took 1806 already and we
just want to review something,

01:05:51.186 --> 01:05:53.806
we can consume that, but
that's not for a ninth grader

01:05:53.806 --> 01:05:56.309
who wants to learn how to learn a matrix.

01:05:56.309 --> 01:05:58.809
For K through 12, I
think that's one reason

01:05:58.809 --> 01:06:01.914
why Khan Academy has picked up,

01:06:01.914 --> 01:06:04.184
because it is directly
addressing its audience.

01:06:04.184 --> 01:06:07.820
I think, on top of that, the
open courseware movement,

01:06:07.820 --> 01:06:10.936
which I think is awesome,
but their first time

01:06:10.936 --> 01:06:12.686
it let's put videos in classrooms.

01:06:12.686 --> 01:06:14.160
They didn't rethink the form factor.

01:06:14.160 --> 01:06:16.463
They didn't say, "Well, is this
really the best way to learn online?"

01:06:16.463 --> 01:06:17.928
We're just saying, "We're
going to show you what goes on

01:06:17.928 --> 01:06:20.232
in an MIT classroom,"
which I think is awesome.

01:06:20.232 --> 01:06:23.732
Audience Member: When it first
came out, it was revolutionary.

01:06:23.732 --> 01:06:24.676
Sal: No, it was.

01:06:24.676 --> 01:06:26.209
That was my proudest day as an alum.

01:06:26.209 --> 01:06:28.583
Audience Member: What I
found is that it seemed to be

01:06:28.583 --> 01:06:30.113
dumping all this information.

01:06:30.113 --> 01:06:33.450
Sal: Yeah, there's two things
that it's going when you go there.

01:06:33.450 --> 01:06:35.519
One is it's hard to navigate.

01:06:35.519 --> 01:06:37.421
You don't know what to watch next,

01:06:37.421 --> 01:06:39.648
so it's not for someone
who's never seen it before.

01:06:39.648 --> 01:06:41.390
There's no direct path
and the other thing is

01:06:41.390 --> 01:06:44.293
even when I was making videos I was
doing the (unintelligible) video.

01:06:44.293 --> 01:06:47.433
This whole time I was like
(unintelligible) MIT stuff.

01:06:47.433 --> 01:06:48.815
I went to the thermodynamics lectures

01:06:48.815 --> 01:06:51.814
and I had to sift through
so much non-entropy talk

01:06:51.814 --> 01:06:53.773
to finally get to entropy
and then finally there was

01:06:53.773 --> 01:06:56.065
an exactly what I want, so
it's very hard to consume.

01:06:56.065 --> 01:06:58.482
Even when you watch the video, I'm not -

01:06:58.482 --> 01:07:00.010
I think it was an awesome thing,

01:07:00.010 --> 01:07:01.565
especially because in 2000 or 2001,

01:07:01.565 --> 01:07:03.732
every other university was doing some type

01:07:03.732 --> 01:07:06.982
of for profit, University
of Phoenix-ish type of thing

01:07:06.982 --> 01:07:09.121
and MIT, it's going to be free.

01:07:09.121 --> 01:07:12.357
I think it's awesome, but
if you watch the videos,

01:07:12.357 --> 01:07:14.897
I probably watched, I think
more than any of you all,

01:07:14.897 --> 01:07:16.730
I watched more open courseware videos.

01:07:16.730 --> 01:07:19.796
Every now and then, the
professor puts up a slide

01:07:19.796 --> 01:07:22.427
that's like, "This is a copyright
issue, you cannot see what this -

01:07:22.427 --> 01:07:26.481
I'm like, "Oh my God, how am I
going to understand?" (laughter)

01:07:26.481 --> 01:07:29.039
It happens one out of every five videos.

01:07:29.039 --> 01:07:31.732
Or the camera is just
not where it should be.

01:07:31.732 --> 01:07:35.278
You can't see -

01:07:35.278 --> 01:07:37.315
I think it's awesome for
other universities to see

01:07:37.315 --> 01:07:39.926
what MIT is doing and it
takes a lot of security

01:07:39.926 --> 01:07:41.686
on the part of MIT to do that -

01:07:41.686 --> 01:07:46.056
Audience Member: It takes some
confidence to release (crosstalk)

01:07:46.056 --> 01:07:48.065
Everything you have, basically.

01:07:48.065 --> 01:07:50.648
Sal: Because it says there's
a value of being here

01:07:50.648 --> 01:07:53.315
and also it's, "Look,
this leaves us open,"

01:07:53.315 --> 01:07:54.897
because before this, everyone would think

01:07:54.897 --> 01:07:57.602
all these secret things are
happening at MIT that are special,

01:07:57.602 --> 01:07:59.815
but now you know exactly what's happening

01:07:59.815 --> 01:08:04.565
and it loses the (unintelligible)
mystique of (unintelligible)

01:08:04.565 --> 01:08:08.345
I agree, but I talked to open courseware

01:08:08.345 --> 01:08:10.514
and I'm open to talking to
them as much as possible.

01:08:10.514 --> 01:08:13.482
I asked them, "Hey, how
about Khan Academy becomes

01:08:13.482 --> 01:08:15.565
"your K through 12 offering?

01:08:15.565 --> 01:08:17.449
"Because this will help recruit
kids, get them interested,

01:08:17.449 --> 01:08:19.947
"I'm an alum and we could get other -

01:08:19.947 --> 01:08:24.047
They were putting video cameras
in the classrooms right now,

01:08:24.047 --> 01:08:27.104
but hopefully that changes.

01:08:27.104 --> 01:08:29.107
I think I would love to
recruit other professors

01:08:29.107 --> 01:08:31.067
to do this form factor,
get other students,

01:08:31.067 --> 01:08:33.977
get you all to do whatever
you all want to do.

01:08:33.977 --> 01:08:41.629
Audience Member:
(unintelligible) (laughter)

01:08:41.629 --> 01:08:42.987
Sal: The questions is how much
of the success of the site

01:08:42.987 --> 01:08:46.212
related to the incompetency of teachers?

01:08:46.212 --> 01:08:50.094
This is a sensitive subject. (laughter)

01:08:50.094 --> 01:08:53.301
Audience Member: (unintelligible)

01:08:53.301 --> 01:08:55.095
Sal: How many teachers
are in the - (laughter)

01:08:55.095 --> 01:08:58.760
The reality is there
are incompetent anybody,

01:08:58.760 --> 01:09:01.260
there are incompetent x, and
unfortunately, some kids,

01:09:01.260 --> 01:09:03.810
that's all they get and I
think there's a lot of that.

01:09:03.810 --> 01:09:05.379
Just look at the -

01:09:05.379 --> 01:09:06.880
The only comments I delete from the site

01:09:06.880 --> 01:09:09.096
are when there's profane
language and even those,

01:09:09.096 --> 01:09:10.483
some I don't get to.

01:09:10.483 --> 01:09:12.451
These are unedited
comments and you'll see,

01:09:12.451 --> 01:09:15.678
on pretty much every video,
at least half the comments

01:09:15.678 --> 01:09:18.558
are some kid who's angry that
they're paying x thousand dollars

01:09:18.558 --> 01:09:22.130
in tuition to whatever and
they spent a whole semester

01:09:22.130 --> 01:09:25.011
trying to learn it and they
thought it was impossible to learn,

01:09:25.011 --> 01:09:27.760
they spent ten minutes on some
video and that's all it was

01:09:27.760 --> 01:09:31.676
and they're angry, they genuinely
want to kill somebody. (laughter)

01:09:31.676 --> 01:09:33.928
I think that's out there.

01:09:33.928 --> 01:09:35.877
A professor in Montreal
wrote a blog post about this.

01:09:35.877 --> 01:09:39.866
It's just like even if you say
this above average instruction.

01:09:39.866 --> 01:09:42.794
We can debate is it better than
90%, is it better than 50%,

01:09:42.794 --> 01:09:44.393
but even if it's above
average instruction,

01:09:44.393 --> 01:09:46.701
even if this instruction
better than 50% of instructors,

01:09:46.701 --> 01:09:49.393
what's the point of having
those 50% of instructors.

01:09:49.393 --> 01:09:52.383
It's a thought experiment
that should happen.

01:09:52.383 --> 01:09:56.342
Even if I'm not the 95th
% instructor, someone is.

01:09:56.342 --> 01:09:57.675
Then you get that person,

01:09:57.675 --> 01:09:59.675
or someone's the 99th
percentile instructor

01:09:59.675 --> 01:10:01.363
and if you have that person,
then why are you having

01:10:01.363 --> 01:10:08.704
the other 99 out of 100 delivering
lectures, but there is -

01:10:08.704 --> 01:10:11.270
It goes into a lot of teachers
are a product of the same system.

01:10:11.270 --> 01:10:13.477
They're products of where
they don't have the intuitions

01:10:13.477 --> 01:10:15.879
and the connections and because
of that, they're passing on

01:10:15.879 --> 01:10:21.003
this rote, superficial understanding
of things for generations.

01:10:21.003 --> 01:11:09.848
Audience Member: (unintelligible)

01:11:09.848 --> 01:11:13.307
Sal: The question, I think,
is is it just going to be me

01:11:13.307 --> 01:11:17.133
or are there other potential people?

01:11:17.133 --> 01:11:20.910
Even the top notch thing, it's
not clear that MIT instruction

01:11:20.910 --> 01:11:25.245
is better than what you're
going to get at the local high -

01:11:25.245 --> 01:11:27.344
Those guys are going to be kick butt,

01:11:27.344 --> 01:11:29.455
in terms of the research
they're doing and all of that,

01:11:29.455 --> 01:11:32.372
but instruction that might
be ideal for an MIT student,

01:11:32.372 --> 01:11:34.150
some of the MIT lectures,
I think they're confident

01:11:34.150 --> 01:11:40.156
because they say, "Look how
hard this class is." (laughter)

01:11:40.156 --> 01:11:42.455
The question about other instructors,

01:11:42.455 --> 01:11:45.329
when I started this, I assumed
that was going to be the case.

01:11:45.329 --> 01:11:47.899
I assumed that I had done
30 videos and I was like,

01:11:47.899 --> 01:11:49.565
"Oh, this is fun and
people are watching it.

01:11:49.565 --> 01:11:52.122
"Let me get my other buddies from
MIT and they'll make some videos

01:11:52.122 --> 01:11:54.071
"and I'll see if they're interested."

01:11:54.071 --> 01:11:55.705
Some were interested,
but it was harder for me

01:11:55.705 --> 01:11:59.205
to get people to do videos than
for me to just do them myself.

01:11:59.205 --> 01:12:02.931
After some point, I had
maybe 100 or 200 videos

01:12:02.931 --> 01:12:05.405
and I said, "This is algebra,
it's pretty much done."

01:12:05.405 --> 01:12:09.776
I said, "I'm just going to keep
going," but I'm open to it.

01:12:09.776 --> 01:12:12.155
If someone wants to -

01:12:12.155 --> 01:12:13.488
A couple people have volunteered, I said,

01:12:13.488 --> 01:12:14.655
"Make 50 videos.

01:12:14.655 --> 01:12:17.100
"If I think those 50 videos
are of the same stock -

01:12:17.100 --> 01:12:19.136
Even if they don't get
associated with Khan Academy,

01:12:19.136 --> 01:12:21.069
they're going to have value by themselves.

01:12:21.069 --> 01:12:22.820
They're going to be on YouTube,
the world can access them.

01:12:22.820 --> 01:12:24.902
If I think they're of the same
style and they're coherent

01:12:24.902 --> 01:12:26.808
with this brand, I'll
push traffic that way,

01:12:26.808 --> 01:12:29.143
especially there's a guy who
just contacted me about music.

01:12:29.143 --> 01:12:30.286
He wants to do a music video.

01:12:30.286 --> 01:12:33.321
I don't know anything about
music (unintelligible)

01:12:33.321 --> 01:12:34.736
until you teach me about music.

01:12:34.736 --> 01:12:39.488
I'm open to it, but I don't
think it's something I could put

01:12:39.488 --> 01:12:43.738
a job posting for (unintelligible)

01:12:43.738 --> 01:12:45.905
The other thing is a lot
of very good instructors

01:12:45.905 --> 01:12:48.071
freeze up a little bit
in this form factor,

01:12:48.071 --> 01:12:50.738
because you are putting
yourself out there.

01:12:50.738 --> 01:12:54.321
If you're a Nobel Prize
PhD, it's a lot harder

01:12:54.321 --> 01:12:56.039
when someone criticizes you than me.

01:12:56.039 --> 01:12:59.106
I'm just a guy, but when
you're the authority,

01:12:59.106 --> 01:13:00.879
to put yourself out there in that way,

01:13:00.879 --> 01:13:04.346
sometimes a little daunting to -

01:13:04.346 --> 01:13:05.571
Audience Member: I don't
know if this is for you

01:13:05.571 --> 01:13:07.071
or your crack programming team,

01:13:07.071 --> 01:13:10.152
but how far away are you from
having forget the videos,

01:13:10.152 --> 01:13:13.926
at least the drilling module
for high school algebra one

01:13:13.926 --> 01:13:16.739
on a DS or an iPod Touch?

01:13:16.739 --> 01:13:19.527
Sal: How far is the module from a -

01:13:19.527 --> 01:13:21.155
Audience Member: Having
a complete drill set,

01:13:21.155 --> 01:13:23.199
all the questions, all the metrics,

01:13:23.199 --> 01:13:25.034
everything being able to load.

01:13:25.034 --> 01:13:30.138
Put junior in the back of the
minivan and do two problems

01:13:30.138 --> 01:13:33.208
every 15 minutes or every five minutes

01:13:33.208 --> 01:13:37.155
and teach junior algebra one
in the back of the minivan,

01:13:37.155 --> 01:13:39.049
all year, not having to go to class.

01:13:39.049 --> 01:13:44.980
Sal: Oh yeah, iPad
(unintelligible) iPad expert.

01:13:44.980 --> 01:13:47.039
I think it's literally -

01:13:47.039 --> 01:13:52.444
We don't have but one developer
for six months devoted on that

01:13:52.444 --> 01:13:54.610
would probably be able to migrate -

01:13:54.610 --> 01:13:55.559
Audience Member: Would
the data fit, though?

01:13:55.559 --> 01:13:56.826
How much data would you need for that?

01:13:56.826 --> 01:13:59.760
Sal: I think it's just a matter of
syncing it and that type of thing,

01:13:59.760 --> 01:14:01.778
it'd just be implementation,
but I think it could easily

01:14:01.778 --> 01:14:04.778
be consumed and done, especially
on an iPad or something like that.

01:14:04.778 --> 01:14:08.028
There's no reason why
that shouldn't be done.

01:14:08.028 --> 01:14:09.406
Audience Member: You're non-profit, right?

01:14:09.406 --> 01:14:10.055
Sal: Yes.

01:14:10.055 --> 01:14:11.507
Audience Member: Do
you see yourself moving

01:14:11.507 --> 01:14:14.809
to a revenue model and
have another approach?

01:14:14.809 --> 01:14:18.028
Sal: Yeah, I'm surprised it
took this long (laughter)

01:14:18.028 --> 01:14:23.195
(unintelligible)

01:14:23.195 --> 01:14:27.323
It's a not for profit, 51C3,
and it was interesting,

01:14:27.323 --> 01:14:29.193
because about a year ago,
before I quit my job,

01:14:29.193 --> 01:14:31.126
I wanted to quit my job.

01:14:31.126 --> 01:14:32.507
It was a good job, but
I wanted to do this,

01:14:32.507 --> 01:14:35.090
and some PCs had contacted me saying,

01:14:35.090 --> 01:14:36.340
"Hey, we love what you're doing

01:14:36.340 --> 01:14:37.674
"and we think you're
doing education right.

01:14:37.674 --> 01:14:39.505
"How about we do a hybrid model?

01:14:39.505 --> 01:14:41.839
"You're going to get a
salary and you can do this.

01:14:41.839 --> 01:14:45.924
" We'll have some premium
content or this or that,"

01:14:45.924 --> 01:14:50.380
and I was very close to doing that,

01:14:50.380 --> 01:14:52.619
but then the more and
more I thought about it,

01:14:52.619 --> 01:14:54.950
especially when I spoke to
them, I knew that at some point

01:14:54.950 --> 01:15:01.173
our desires were going to
conflict and my worst nightmare

01:15:01.173 --> 01:15:04.726
is that all these videos I
did, all of this gets acquired

01:15:04.726 --> 01:15:07.231
by McGraw-Hill (laughter)
and it gets thrown

01:15:07.231 --> 01:15:11.153
in some library someplace and
just disappears from the planet.

01:15:11.153 --> 01:15:13.840
For me, the real joy of this,
even if I'm forced to drive

01:15:13.840 --> 01:15:17.673
a used Honda my entire life, is
that my great-great-grandkids

01:15:17.673 --> 01:15:20.340
might be able to learn
calculus from these videos.

01:15:20.340 --> 01:15:23.675
That, to me, is the most
tremendously exciting powerful thing.

01:15:23.675 --> 01:15:28.285
It is not for profit, it was being funded
by my bank account until very recently.

01:15:28.285 --> 01:15:32.220
Actually, last week, Ann and John Doerr

01:15:32.220 --> 01:15:35.396
wrote a $100,000 check
to give me a salary,

01:15:35.396 --> 01:15:39.561
so you don't have to do too much.

01:15:39.561 --> 01:15:43.871
I'll take some sandwiches, but I'm okay.

01:15:43.871 --> 01:15:45.869
I'm talking to some fairly
large corporations now

01:15:45.869 --> 01:15:47.257
that they're like, "Yeah, this -

01:15:47.257 --> 01:15:53.041
I tell them, "Show me a higher
social return on an investment."

01:15:53.041 --> 01:15:57.339
Get half a million dollar budget,
we'll have three, four developers,

01:15:57.339 --> 01:16:00.117
we can educate millions
of kids for all time.

01:16:00.117 --> 01:16:01.590
It's not like this is a charter school

01:16:01.590 --> 01:16:04.220
and as soon as the money
disappears the school disappears.

01:16:04.220 --> 01:16:05.730
As long as someone's paying $50 a month

01:16:05.730 --> 01:16:09.089
for the web hosting (laughter)
it's going to exist forever.

01:16:09.089 --> 01:16:12.255
Now it's being replicated on this, it's
getting on all sorts of hard drives

01:16:12.255 --> 01:16:13.895
and we're going to put it on
BitTorrent and all of that,

01:16:13.895 --> 01:16:15.965
so we don't even have to
pay for the web hosting.

01:16:15.965 --> 01:16:18.867
You're building a library that can
continue to deliver social returns.

01:16:18.867 --> 01:16:23.240
You do any type of (unintelligible)
it's like $500,000 per year investment,

01:16:23.240 --> 01:16:26.509
the social return is going to be,
especially if you translate it

01:16:26.509 --> 01:16:30.884
into five languages, it's
like $5 billion a year,

01:16:30.884 --> 01:16:32.674
if you associate a video view with $1.

01:16:32.674 --> 01:16:36.175
It's ridiculous and I hope
people are seeing that.

01:16:36.175 --> 01:16:38.010
Hopefully we'll get some.

01:16:38.010 --> 01:16:39.593
Audience Member: (unintelligible)

01:16:39.593 --> 01:16:42.175
Sal: I am not going to
sell out. (laughter)

01:16:42.175 --> 01:16:47.469
There might be a movie one day. (laughter)

01:16:47.469 --> 01:16:48.736
Hopefully I won't sell out.

01:16:48.736 --> 01:16:51.972
Audience Member: To follow
on that a little bit,

01:16:51.972 --> 01:16:54.093
you told us a number
of ways that education

01:16:54.093 --> 01:16:58.414
is entrenched in productive ways.

01:16:58.414 --> 01:17:02.051
Is this interesting in a
way Wikipedia's interesting

01:17:02.051 --> 01:17:04.633
or is it interesting
in ways that can end up

01:17:04.633 --> 01:17:09.490
transforming education as it exists today?

01:17:09.490 --> 01:17:16.699
This would be good supplemental
material (unintelligible) (crosstalk)

01:17:16.699 --> 01:17:18.084
Sal: I'll repeat it.

01:17:18.084 --> 01:17:22.334
The question is do I envision
this as being what Wikipedia is,

01:17:22.334 --> 01:17:25.039
which is a tremendous
impact, but a supplemental,

01:17:25.039 --> 01:17:27.308
nice to have for the
world, or is this something

01:17:27.308 --> 01:17:31.097
that could transform education?

01:17:31.097 --> 01:17:33.093
I think in the short term it's the former,

01:17:33.093 --> 01:17:36.240
but in the long term, and for
me long term is ten years,

01:17:36.240 --> 01:17:37.407
I think it really is -

01:17:37.407 --> 01:17:40.210
A big part of this, I view
this as the operating system

01:17:40.210 --> 01:17:41.844
with the DNA for a physical school

01:17:41.844 --> 01:17:46.928
and I actually do a little summer
camp, really for me to experiment

01:17:46.928 --> 01:17:49.594
with what you do with the
rest of the school day,

01:17:49.594 --> 01:17:51.655
because I can do this for
two hours and then it frees

01:17:51.655 --> 01:17:54.625
the rest of the time for creative things,
to actually write computer programs,

01:17:54.625 --> 01:17:58.657
compose music, paint, to
actually build things.

01:17:58.657 --> 01:18:01.761
My goal is that summer
camp's going to get longer

01:18:01.761 --> 01:18:04.067
and longer and longer. (laughter)

01:18:04.067 --> 01:18:07.703
Actually, the San Jose Tech Museum
is going to give us some space.

01:18:07.703 --> 01:18:11.119
We're going to start
having a presence there.

01:18:11.119 --> 01:18:14.457
That physical experiment's going
to get more and more substantial

01:18:14.457 --> 01:18:15.883
and at some point, we're going to be like,

01:18:15.883 --> 01:18:18.496
"We're a real school now
and this is the prototype,"

01:18:18.496 --> 01:18:24.048
and I don't want to do it if it's
only 5% better outcomes than what -

01:18:24.048 --> 01:18:28.904
I want kids, "Hey, I just
painted that picture,

01:18:28.904 --> 01:18:31.006
"I just built that robot,
and by the way I'm 12

01:18:31.006 --> 01:18:32.466
"and I'm learning calculus."

01:18:32.466 --> 01:18:35.632
I want to see that and I think
once you have one example of that,

01:18:35.632 --> 01:18:40.716
but I think (unintelligible)
Then I think you set the example

01:18:40.716 --> 01:18:41.966
and I think the rest of the
world's going to be like,

01:18:41.966 --> 01:18:45.354
"Wait, even our $40,000 a year fancy
private school is not doing that

01:18:45.354 --> 01:18:49.326
"and they're charging $5,000
a student," as opposed to -

01:18:49.326 --> 01:18:51.134
Audience Member: Then the
next question that comes,

01:18:51.134 --> 01:18:54.668
if you do that, this seems to
apply to self-selecting students

01:18:54.668 --> 01:18:57.934
who seek out the materials and
even in the case of the camp,

01:18:57.934 --> 01:19:02.298
obviously there's some selection there.

01:19:02.298 --> 01:19:06.765
How applicable are the ideas then of
going through school (unintelligible)

01:19:06.765 --> 01:19:09.227
Sal: Right, the idea is
this is right now applicable

01:19:09.227 --> 01:19:10.634
to a self-selecting pool of students

01:19:10.634 --> 01:19:13.838
and even the summer camp
I'm doing and that's true

01:19:13.838 --> 01:19:16.142
and how do you apply it to a broader -

01:19:16.142 --> 01:19:17.808
I think there's two -

01:19:17.808 --> 01:19:20.709
The summer camp that I
showed the data with,

01:19:20.709 --> 01:19:23.374
the selection criteria was
not kids with a certain IQ

01:19:23.374 --> 01:19:24.710
or kids who've done -

01:19:24.710 --> 01:19:28.101
That was just non-problem kids.

01:19:28.101 --> 01:19:30.628
This was mainly minority
kids from east Palo Alto,

01:19:30.628 --> 01:19:34.709
Redwood City, Menlo Park, who they
didn't have discipline problems,

01:19:34.709 --> 01:19:40.415
but I think that could describe 80%
of students, probably 90% of students.

01:19:40.415 --> 01:19:42.814
I'd say problem the subset
that have discipline problems,

01:19:42.814 --> 01:19:45.252
a lot of it is because they're
not being addressed in this way

01:19:45.252 --> 01:19:46.919
that they have these gaps
and no one can address it

01:19:46.919 --> 01:19:49.189
and there's all sorts of social stigmas.

01:19:49.189 --> 01:19:52.424
It's ridiculous that concepts
and age are associated

01:19:52.424 --> 01:19:54.927
in this tightly linked way that
if you're 13 and you need help

01:19:54.927 --> 01:19:59.332
with decimals you're stupid and
I'm going to make fun of you.

01:19:59.332 --> 01:20:01.464
I think that leads to a lot of
social acting out and all that.

01:20:01.464 --> 01:20:05.048
Actually, I want to get this into prisons,

01:20:05.048 --> 01:20:15.109
because they have a
lot of time. (laughter)

01:20:15.109 --> 01:20:18.246
I don't know the exact answer,
there would be some experimentation,

01:20:18.246 --> 01:20:20.016
but I suspect that this is going to appeal

01:20:20.016 --> 01:20:23.585
to a larger swath
because it's interactive.

01:20:23.585 --> 01:20:25.969
Everything about it, you're
never having to sit passively.

01:20:25.969 --> 01:20:28.139
You're learning the way people
naturally want to learn.

01:20:28.139 --> 01:20:30.859
I think a lot of these
hyperactive kids or whatever,

01:20:30.859 --> 01:20:34.628
they're natural learners, they
just don't like being lectured to.

01:20:34.628 --> 01:20:38.305
They like to be interactive and
talk to their peers and whatnot.

01:20:38.305 --> 01:20:42.964
We'll see where that goes,
but it's an interesting seed.

01:20:42.964 --> 01:20:44.294
It's an interesting question.

01:20:44.294 --> 01:20:46.576
If there is something that can really
accelerate 90% of the students,

01:20:46.576 --> 01:20:48.792
but it leaves behind 10%, is
that a good or a bad thing

01:20:48.792 --> 01:20:53.130
and that's a whole social
debate that one could have.

01:20:53.130 --> 01:20:54.963
Audience Member: In case there
is a movie made about you,

01:20:54.963 --> 01:20:57.988
can the other Salman Khan
play this Salman Khan.

01:20:57.988 --> 01:21:01.158
Sal: Oh yeah, he says,
"Can the other Salman -

01:21:01.158 --> 01:21:03.093
For those who've never done
a web search for Salman Khan,

01:21:03.093 --> 01:21:04.547
I encourage you to do so when you go home,

01:21:04.547 --> 01:21:06.880
because there's an Indian
actor with my name.

01:21:06.880 --> 01:21:12.390
I think that's helped me beat MIT
open courseware, as well. (laughter)

01:21:12.390 --> 01:21:15.424
Audience Member: One issue
you might have thought about,

01:21:15.424 --> 01:21:17.868
I've watched a second
grader in the neighborhood

01:21:17.868 --> 01:21:21.118
who is homeschooled and I'm
afraid he's really missing out

01:21:21.118 --> 01:21:25.901
on the socialization factor.

01:21:25.901 --> 01:21:28.687
If we transition more to
this method of teaching,

01:21:28.687 --> 01:21:31.792
how would we not lose that?

01:21:31.792 --> 01:21:33.734
Sal: Right, so the question's
on socialization factor.

01:21:33.734 --> 01:21:36.150
I want to be very clear,
this is on the internet,

01:21:36.150 --> 01:21:38.432
essentially and someone could
be sitting in an isolated room

01:21:38.432 --> 01:21:40.299
and doing this and not
having any socialization,

01:21:40.299 --> 01:21:44.316
but the goal when I described
the one room schoolhouse

01:21:44.316 --> 01:21:46.214
is that it actually is social.

01:21:46.214 --> 01:21:50.008
For the first time, you actually
do get socialization in a school.

01:21:50.008 --> 01:21:52.735
Most of us, there's a thousand
kids in the schoolhouse,

01:21:52.735 --> 01:21:57.025
but you don't get any interaction,
especially in a meaty way,

01:21:57.025 --> 01:21:59.671
except in recess and lunch, but
now this is actually encouraging

01:21:59.671 --> 01:22:02.194
socialization in the classroom,
where you're tutoring each other.

01:22:02.194 --> 01:22:05.877
That's actually very good socialization.

01:22:05.877 --> 01:22:10.487
If you think about when do you want
to give someone a big thumbs up?

01:22:10.487 --> 01:22:12.821
Right now, the system
says, "Oh, you're a genius,

01:22:12.821 --> 01:22:14.089
"you got an 800 on your SAT."

01:22:14.089 --> 01:22:15.533
That's where you get the thumbs up,

01:22:15.533 --> 01:22:17.356
but the real thumbs up
is you're a good teacher,

01:22:17.356 --> 01:22:19.571
you have empathy, you have maturity.

01:22:19.571 --> 01:22:22.904
When other kids respect you
for your ability to communicate

01:22:22.904 --> 01:22:24.654
and not talk down to them.

01:22:24.654 --> 01:22:28.934
If you think about what
people will get points for,

01:22:28.934 --> 01:22:31.633
I want it to be that, that
the data and assessments show

01:22:31.633 --> 01:22:33.987
that you're a great teacher to your peers.

01:22:33.987 --> 01:22:38.011
If you're an employer or a
university, those are the kids

01:22:38.011 --> 01:22:41.571
you want to admit, not the
kid who's just racing ahead

01:22:41.571 --> 01:22:44.070
and just arrogant and all of that.

01:22:44.070 --> 01:22:49.195
I think it will actually help
socialization, especially
the one room model.

01:22:52.984 --> 01:22:53.890
Oh, yeah.

